<DOCNO> XIE19970726.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EMEAP Convenes In Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 25 (Xinhua) -- The governors of 11 central banks
and monetary authorities in the Asia/Pacific region expressed
their hope here today for increased cooperation to stabilize the
regional currency markets in times of emergency.
</P>
<P>
They discussed the recent developments in currency markets in
East Asia during the one-day closed-door meeting of the second
governors' meeting of the Executives' Meeting of East Asia and the
Pacific (EMEAP).
</P>
<P>
The conference is attended by banking officials from Australia,
China, Hong Kong, Indonesia, Japan, the Republic of Korea (ROK),
Malaysia, New Zealand, the Philippines, Singapore and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The governors reached consensus that central banks in the
region should give due attention to the factor of price
fluctuation in stock markets, real estate and other assets,
besides the traditional price indexes, when making monetary
policies.
</P>
<P>
Dai Xianglong, governor of the People's Bank of China, noted
after the meeting that the governors particularly emphasized
stabilizing the foreign currency market and making active efforts
to guard against speculative encroachments on the foreign exchange
markets in the region.
</P>
<P>
The governors also held that it is essential for member
countries to further increase cooperation in a bid to help
stabilize the regional currency markets, Dai added.
</P>
<P>
As part of such efforts, a computer secretariat will be set up
after the meeting, so as to help the EMEAP members share information.
</P>
<P>
The governors also affirmed during the session that a series of
major coordinations and adjustments made by member countries were
positive in coping with the challenge of the recent developments
in regional currency market.
</P>
<P>
So it is fairly appropriate not to consider admitting new
members to the EMEAP at the meeting, since all the bank governors
present regarded the organization as still in its preliminary
stage of development, and this is conducive for the member countries
to have a candid exchange of views.
</P>
<P>
The officials also stressed on the importance of improving
cooperation with the International Monetary Fund and the
Federation Reserve System (FRS) of the United States.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the EMEAP has decided to hold a separate session with
the FRS at its 14th meeting of deputy governors of the central
banks of member countries, which will is expected to be held in
the Philippines in November this year.
</P>
<P>
EMEAP was established in 1991 to provide its members with
chances to exchange views on regional economic and monetary issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
