<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five Feared Dead after Apartment House Explosion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 25 (Xinhua) -- At least five people were feared dead
in a suspected natural gas explosion which destroyed a four-story
apartment house in the western Germany city of Duesseldorf on
Thursday, reports reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
After rescuing two people alive and recovering three bodies
from the debris on Thursday, Rescue workers using special cameras
and sniffer dogs found another body and located a possible fifth
on Friday, police said.
</P>
<P>
Police later also corrected the number of residents registered
as living in the house from 15 to 14. Seven of them are believed
to be on vacation and two at work at the time of the explosion at
about 3:00 a.m. Thursday.
</P>
<P>
However, it remains unclear so far how many are still buried
under the ruins because fire fighters on Thursday night found five
identity cards which do not belong to the 14 registered residents.
</P>
<P>
The building is the only one in the street that is not
connected to the public gas supplies. But a gas pipe powering
street lights runs just in front of the house. Gas explosion is
suspected because of a strong smell of natural gas immediately
after the accident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
