<HEADLINE> Ukraine's Orphanages Need More Assistance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, July 25 (Xinhua) -- The number of children in Ukraine's
overcrowded and poorly financed orphanages grew by 10-15 percent
in 1996, local newspapers reported today.
</P>
<P>
A survey, conducted by the International Women's Club and the
Kiev-Mohyla Academy School of Social Work in 109 orphanages and
boarding schools in May, showed that most of the children in the
orphanages were abandoned by their parents.
</P>
<P>
There were many cases of parents refusing to claim their
new-born babies from hospitals or abandoning children with mental
and physical disabilities.
</P>
<P>
At the Dnepropetrovsk orphanage for babies with nervous system
and psychological disorders, 77 of the 200 orphans in residence
were abandoned by their parents, while 37 came from families which
could not afford them and 35 were removed from parental custody
under the law.
</P>
<P>
The survey also revealed that orphanages housing 300-400
children aged seven and above have problems of getting clothes and
textbooks.
</P>
<P>
Many orphanages and boarding schools in the country are
receiving foreign and domestic non-governmental assistance.
</P>
<P>
A boarding school hosting 280 children in the village of
Beregin of Zakarpattia received medicines, clothes and hygienic
items from Holland, Denmark and Norway in April, and it also
received medicines from a charity run by Lyudmia Kuchma, wife of
Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma.
</P>
<P>
Banks, private companies, state enterprises and government
employees are also active in contributing foods, clothing and
money to the orphanages and boarding schools.
</P>
<P>
However, most orphanages and boarding schools in Ukraine still
lack sponsors and humanitarian assistance.
</P>
<P>
The survey said that adoption is rare in the country, with only
four of the 300 children at the boarding school in the village of
Vovkovintsy, Khmelnytsky Oblast, were adopted last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
