<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dublin, Sinn Fein Urge Unionists to Stay in Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern
and Sinn Fein President Gerry Adams today jointly urged Northern
Ireland's unionists to stay in the peace talks to salvage the
fragile peace process.
</P>
<P>
After an hour of talks in Dublin, Ahern, Adams and leader of
Northern Ireland's Catholic Social Democratic and Labor Party John
Hume made a joint statement, appealing to the pro-British
unionists to back a struggling talks initiative aimed at ending
decades of strife with pro-Irish republicans.
</P>
<P>
"We recognize that ultimately we can resolve this problem only
with the participation and agreement of the unionist people," the
three leaders said in a statement which Ahern read to journalists.
</P>
<P>
Irish Republican Army (IRA), which has been fighting against
the British rule of Northern Ireland over the past 28 years,
called a ceasefire last weekend so as to gain a seat in September
peace talks for its political wing Sinn Fein.
</P>
<P>
However, the peace process was dealt a blow when the Protestant
unionist parties voted against the arms surrendering plans on
Wednesday in protest of Sinn Fein's participation in the peace
talks without a commitment to disarm.
</P>
<P>
Ahern hoped London and Dublin could persuade the unionists, who
speak for Northern Ireland's majority Protestants, to stay in the
talks -- which Sinn Fein will be allowed to join on September 15
if the IRA ceasefire is judged genuine.
</P>
<P>
"It is very important that the two governments remain in the
driving seat. I hope we can find a way to give satisfactory bona
fides to the unionists and Trimble to get them to come to the
September 15 talks," Ahern said.
</P>
<P>
The British government said that peace talks on Northern
Ireland's future will go ahead despite unionists' opposition to
the arms surrender plans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
