<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strong Pound Is Hitting UK's Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 25 (Xinhua) -- The pound's rise on the foreign
exchanges markets has had a dramatic impact on export orders and
is threatening to cause a sharp slowdown in Britain's economy,
according to the Confederation of British Industry (CBI).
</P>
<P>
In its latest quarterly survey, the CBI said that exporters are
pessimistic about prospects than at any time since 1980. Orders
are falling faster than at any time since 1991.
</P>
<P>
The CBI said 39 percent of manufacturers reported a fall in
export orders while 19 percent recorded a rise. That gives a
negative balance of 20 percent, compared with 7 percent for the
four months to April and 1 percent in January.
</P>
<P>
However, factory output is expected to continue increasing as
domestic orders are rising at their fastest rate for more than two
years.
</P>
<P>
Andrew Buxton, chairman of the CBI's economic affairs
committee, said the dichotomy between weak export and strong
domestic demand left the Bank of England facing a tough decision
on monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
But Buxton concluded that "any interest rate rise in the short
term would be unwelcome".
</P>
<P>
City analysts believe the High Street boom will force the Bank
of England to raise interest rates for the fourth time when it
meets on August 7.
</P>
<P>
The latest survey was carried out between June 20 and July 9,
at which time the pound averaged DM2.91 and 1.67$. Since then
sterling has continued to appreciate against the D-Mark.
</P>
<P>
Despite the strength of the pound, Britain's trade performance
improved in May. The trade gap with the rest of the world narrowed
to 500 million pounds (800 million US dollars), according to the
latest data released by the Office for National Statistics.
</P>
<P>
Imports fell 5.5 percent from April's record levels to 14.6
billion pounds (23.16 billion US dollars) while exports, fell by
2.5 percent to 14.1 billion pounds (22.56 billion US dollars) in
May.
</P>
<P>
Although the figures showed do sign yet of an export slowdown
due to the strong pound, economists predicted that this was only a
matter of time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
