<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Kenya's Financial Market Stable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 25 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan currency Shilling is
gradually strengthening and the depreciation of Shilling has been
reversed with posting marginal gains against the U.S Dollar.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank of Kenya (CBK) posted a mean Shilling rate of
58.57 against the Dollar on Thursday, compared with 58.81 on
previous day.
</P>
<P>
By Thursday afternoon, dealers were selling the Dollar at
58.40 as exporters were eager to sell their Dollars and importers
opted to stay out of the market hoping to buy dollars later at a
cheaper rate.
</P>
<P>
The Shilling had suffered significant loss since July 7 when
opposition parties in the country organized mass rallies to press
for constitutional reforms in Nairobi and some other cities.
</P>
<P>
The Shilling rate versus the Dollar had eased to as low as 62
and some commercial banks had exhausted their stock because of
panic buying triggered off by speculators.
</P>
<P>
On July 11, the Central Bank of Kenya had to intervene in the
market by providing 29 million Dollars into the market, which was
believed to be the largest amount of Dollars the CBK has sold to
calm a jittery market for several years.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the Nairobi Stock Exchange (NSE) has started to
stabilize with the number of shares traded on July 14 increasing
to 766,000 from 365,000 on July 11.
</P>
<P>
Following Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi's meeting with 17
religious leaders and the leader of the Official Opposition
Wamalwa Kijana, "greater stability has been apparent in the
financial market."
</P>
<P>
A statement issued Thursday by Kenyan Finance Minister Musalia
Mudavadi and CBK Governor Micah Cheserem said that "some of the
depreciation of the Shilling has been reversed and the Nairobi
Stock Exchange has registered an increase in activity."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, CBK Governor Cheserem has been re-appointed to
another four-year term of office, said the "Kenya Gazzete" issued
Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that the announcement of the
re-appointment was expected to help calm local financial markets
which have been nervous due to the turbulence sparked by
constitutional reform calls.
</P>
<P>
Cheserem took over as governor in 1993 at the height of
financial mismanagement in the banking system and accusations of
corruption at the Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
He then moved to restore discipline, helping to reduce money
supply and cut inflation to current single-digit figures from
around 101 percent in October 1993.
</P>
<P>
The CBK governor said last Wednesday that the Kenyan economy
was stable even after the recent riots which rocked parts of the
country resulting in the steepest depreciation of the Shilling in
recent years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
