<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1998 Hong Kong Rugby Sevens Set for March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 25 (Xinhua) -- One of Hong Kong's famed
sporting events -- Hong Kong Rugby Sevens -- will be held next
March after signing a sponsorship agreement here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The three-year agreement between the Hong Kong Rugby Football
Union (HKRFU) and the Peregrine Investment Holdings will anchor
the tournament's future into the next millennium, as organizers
put it.
</P>
<P>
The HKRFU also announced that the 1998 event of the Hong Kong
Rugby Sevens will be set for March 27-29 in the Hong Kong Stadium,
 with a prize money of five million U.S. dollars on offer for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
"Peregrine's involvement allows us to further raise the high
profile reputation of the Hong Kong Sevens which in turn enables
us to encourage further the expansion of the game both locally and
regionally," said Peter Duncan, Chairman of the HKRFU.
</P>
<P>
"We are embarking on a new era in Hong Kong as the handover is
completed and the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region has been
established," said Philip Tose, Chairman of Peregrine.
</P>
<P>
"The Peregrine Group feels it is appropriate that a new title
sponsor is stepping forward in a long-term commitment to a
tournament that, to so many, means Hong Kong. Our sponsorship is
in keeping with our never wavering faith in this great city and
world-class financial center. We have, if you like, picked up the
ball," he added.
</P>
<P>
After 23 years, Hong Kong Rugby Sevens has become the world's
largest and most popular Sevens rugby event.
</P>
<P>
Next year's event would revert back to the successful 1996
formula, which means six pools of four teams for the
preliminaries. The 24 teams split into six pools according to
their performance will have a single round-robin play within the
pools and then enter the Cup, Plate and Bowl finals according to
the pool performance.
</P>
<P>
China, which joined in the International Rugby Football Board
in March this year, is one of the teams to be invited to the 1998
event, organizers said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Rugby Football Association has applied to join in
the Asian Rugby Football Union (ARFU) which has now eight members.
</P>
<P>
The application is scheduled to be discussed at the ARFU's
annual meeting in December in Singapore, HKRFU officials
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
