<HEADLINE> International Community Won't Accept S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, July 25 (Xinhua) -- U.S Ambassador to Sierra Leone
John Hirsch said today that the international community will not
accept the continued presence of the (military) government in
Freetown and does not recognise it in any way.
</P>
<P>
The statement, issued from the neighboring Guinea, was carried
by the clandestine pro-democracy radio set up by Nigeria in
support of ousted President Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
Hirsch, who was in Guinea since the May 25 coup, said the
almost seven-week strike has shown people's determination to see
the democratically elected government of Kabbah back.
</P>
<P>
The central issue now seems to be whether the military
government and the former rebel combatants genuinely have the
interest of the people of Sierra leone at heart, he said.
</P>
<P>
If they do, they will certainly step down and spare the
people, in whose interest they claimed to have done what they
did, further pains and suffering, he added.
</P>
<P>
Another round of talks between the junta representatives and
the ECOWAS committee on Sierra Leone will be held in Abidjan,
capital of the Ivory Coast on July 29 to work out modalities for
the junta to restore constitutional order in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a junta spokesman denied a claim by Nigeria that
the Sierra Leone army and former rebels were violating the
ceasefire agreement in a series of bloody clashes throughout the
country.
</P>
<P>
"There has been no clashes. We are abiding by the ceasefire
agreement," said Major John Milton, deputy director of defense
information in an interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"Maybe the Nigerians have some motives up their sleeves. It is
there own imagination," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
