<HEADLINE> PNA Reacts Strongly to Jewish Housing Plan in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 25 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) reacted strongly today to Jerusalem municipality's
decision to authorize a Jewish housing plan in East Jerusalem,
warning this will kill the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Jerusalem's hardline Mayor Ehud Olmert confirmed at a news
conference here today that he had authorized American
entrepreneur Irving Moskowitz to carry out the plan to build 70
Jewish housing units in the Arab neighborhood of Ras Amud near
Mount of Olives, citing that Moskowitz had obtained all necessary
permits for the project.
</P>
<P>
The planned housing project immediately sparked strong reaction
from Palestinian officials, who warned that it would end the
already stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
PNA President Yasser Arafat said in Gaza today that he was
watching the developments closely and would hold urgent talks
with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak during his visit to Cairo
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's spokesman Abu Rudeineh denounced the housing plan as
"an attempt by Israeli extremists to destroy the peace process."
Arafat's adviser on Israeli affairs Ahmed Tibi said the plan was a
"declaration of war" against Palestinians in East Jerusalem and in
general.
</P>
<P>
Chief Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat sent a letter of
protest to Israel's Prime Minister's Office, saying the plan must
be scraped if the peace process was to be salvaged. He has also
sent letters to officials in the United States, European Union and
the United Nations to seek their support to stop the Ras Amud
project.
</P>
<P>
To calm the situation, Israeli Prime Minister's Office
announced today that Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu had asked
his adviser Yitzhak Molcho to talk to Arafat, promising he would
take steps to stop the project.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's spokesman David Bar-Illan said that, although the
Israeli government insisted on its rights to build settlements
anywhere in Jerusalem, it held that this was not an opportune time
to carry out the Ras Amud housing plan. He added Netanyahu would
invoke laws on public safety and national security to prevent the
plan at this time.
</P>
<P>
The housing project triggered different reactions from Israel's
leftist and rightist political camps.
</P>
<P>
Some rightist coalition lawmakers welcomed and expressed their
support to the plan. Hanan Porat of the National Religious Party
called it a brave move to authorize the housing project. Rehavam
Zeevi, leader of the ultra-rightist Moledet Party, said building
in Ras Amud was as legal as France's building in Paris and
Britain's building in London.
</P>
<P>
But leftist politicians expressed grave concern about serious
consequences that would be caused by the housing project on the
moribund peace process.
</P>
<P>
The opposition Labor Party leader, Ehud Barak, said the plan was
reminiscent of the decision to open the underground Hasmonean
tunnel in East Jerusalem last September, which sparked a
widespread Israeli-Palestinian confrontation. But Barak welcomed
the announcement by the Prime Minister's Office on the
government's opposition to the plan.
</P>
<P>
Yossi Sarid, leader of the leftist Meretz Party, blasted the
Ras Amud project for being part of the city's inappropriate
policy which began with opening the underground Hasmonean tunnel
and continued with the construction of the Har Homa settlement in
East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The opening of Hasmonean tunnel in East Jerusalem last
September triggered a widespread Israeli-Palestinian violent
confrontation which killed over 70 people and wounded nearly
1,000 others, and the Har Homa construction has totally frozen
the peace process since mid-March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
