<HEADLINE> Four Ministers Appointed by Liberian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, July 25 (Xinhua) - Liberia's president-elect Charles
Taylor today appointed four ministers for his cabinet to be in
charge of foreign affairs, justice, presidential affairs and
information.
</P>
<P>
The rest will be appointed by the weekend.
</P>
<P>
In a press conference in Monrovia, Taylor said, the Liberian
people are one struggling for one destiny. There is need for
every Liberian to join the new government in rebuilding the
nation, not only for themselves, but for the coming generation.
</P>
<P>
He called on all combatants in Liberia including United
Liberation of Liberia for Democracy (ULIMO), the Liberian Peace
Council and the Lofa Defense Force, to make peace in Liberia a
reality.
</P>
<P>
Liberia has remained calm after the election, with heavily
armed west African peacekeeping troops (ECOMOG) patrolling main
streets and towns, and there is unlikely to be any disturbances
after the election.
</P>
<P>
Journalists in the capital said many Liberians have breathed a
sigh of relief that the elections are now over.
</P>
<P>
Taylor's election has been greeted with restrained feeling but
more generally welcomed by the Nigerian-dominated ECOMOG,
political analysts said.
</P>
<P>
International election monitors described the election as
relatively free and fair.
</P>
<P>
"There is no substance in any allegation of fraud," said
former U.S President Jimmy Carter in Monrovia.
</P>
<P>
U.S Senator Paul Simon was "extremely impressed with the level
of enthusiasm exhibited by Liberians at the polls," while the
Organisation of African Unity (OAU) observer team described the
polls as "decent and devoid of violence and irregularities."
</P>
