<HEADLINE> Pakistan Vows to Continue Mediation Efforts for Afghan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 25 (Xinhua) -- A senior Pakistani diplomat said
today that his country will resume its shuttle diplomacy for the
restoration of peace in Afghanistan when he travels to the
war-torn country early next week.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue our efforts to persuade the Afghan factions
to a negotiated settlement of the conflict and restore peace in
the brotherly country," Additional Foreign Secretary Iftikhar
Murshed told the media.
</P>
<P>
Murshed said Pakistan's consultations with the Afghan Islamic
Taliban militia and their northern rivals had yielded positive
results as both sides affirmed their commitment to a peaceful
settlement of the Afghan conflict.
</P>
<P>
Murshed had been scheduled to come back to Mazar-e-Sharif,
headquarters of the anti-Taliban northern alliance, on Saturday at
the head of a Pakistani delegation, but has deferred his trip
until early next week. No reason was given for the postponement.
</P>
<P>
Murshed last traveled to Mazar-e-Sharif early this month and
held talks with the leaders of the alliance including ousted
Afghan president Burhanuddin Rabbani and Uzbek warlord Abdul
Malik. He also had a ground-breaking meeting with former military
chief Ahmad Masood in Farkhar Valley.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Murshed held talks with the Taliban leadership in
Kandahar.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has regretted the recent outbreak of fighting in the
war-ravaged Afghanistan, but vowed to carry on its efforts to
broker peace among warring factions.
</P>
<P>
"The fighting will have no impact on our determination to
continue with the shuttle mission," a spokesman for the Foreign
Office told a weekly news conference here Thursday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
