<HEADLINE> Cyprus Welcomes Greek's Statement on Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 25 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government has
expressed satisfaction with Greece's statement that it would not
rule out the possibility of exercising its right to veto
European Union (EU) membership for Central and Eastern Europe
applicant countries, if Cyprus is excluded from the next move of
EU enlargement.
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Manolis Christofides told his daily press
briefing here today that Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis'
statement appeared in the Financial Times Thursday "absolutely
satisfies us."
</P>
<P>
He said that the Greek premier has reaffirmed "Greece's firm
and decisive policy toward a Cyprus solution and our efforts to
join the EU."
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Financial Times, Simitis said he
hoped it would not be necessary for Greece to veto EU membership
for former Communist countries, since the lengthy accession
procedure would allow considerable time to work out a political
solution in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
He also insisted that the accession talks, due to start early
in 1998, should continue in parallel with efforts to reunite the
divided island.
</P>
<P>
This Eastern Mediterranean island has been divided since 1974
when Turkish troops invaded and took over the northern third in
the wake of a pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, Simitis rejected Turkish threats to derail talks
on a Cyprus settlement if the EU goes ahead with accession
negotiations with the Cypriot government, noting that Greece will
use all measures offered in the framework of the EU to achieve
what it considers to be right.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot spokesman said the Greek premier's interview
"clarifies some questions raised with this month's Madrid
agreement and reiterates Greece's support to Cyprus and its
struggle."
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month on the sidelines of the NATO summit in
Madrid, Greece and Turkey agreed to "settle disputes by peaceful
means based on mutual consent and without use of force and
threat of force." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
