<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 90 Percent of Africa's Debt to Be Forgiven </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 25 (Xinhua) -- About 90 percent or 270 billion
U.S. dollars of Africa's external debt will be forgiven during
the implementation of the 20 year Sub-Saharan African Plan
(1996-2016) formulated with African African-American summit
movement's efforts.
</P>
<P>
The plan, aimed at developing the region to compete with
others in the 21st century, would ensure the remaining 10 percent
or 30 billion U.S. dollars of Africa's debt to remain in the
books.
</P>
<P>
And the interest of three percent on the remaining debt would
be converted annually into local currencies and used for
education and human development.
</P>
<P>
According to the development plan summary published in a
magazine released at the Fourth African African-American summit
in Harare today, the plan which would cost about 500 billion U.S.
dollars would also propose ways to convert debt to development
purposes.
</P>
<P>
By the end of the plan, an estimated two million jobs in the
sub-region were expected to have been created in manufacturing,
agriculture and informal sectors, among others.
</P>
<P>
Another 250,000 jobs are expected to be created in the U.S.
and other participating countries during the plan's
implementation period.
</P>
<P>
The plan would, therefore, develop strategies to encourage
social development, capital investment, expansion of the banking
system's capacity, creation of market economies and
revitalisation of human resources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970726.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands Flee Floods in Germany after More Dikes Burst </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 25 (Xinhua) -- About 9,500 people have to leave
their homes for safety on Friday after rising floodwaters burst
banks at several locations along the Oder River on the
German-Polish border.
</P>
<P>
After a second dike burst near the town of Aurich in the
southern part of the Oder, floodwaters were rushing through an
800-metre gap, flooding homes up to their rooftops. About 2,800
local residents were forced to leave the area.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in Oderbruch in the north, another dike was
threatening to break, and 6,500 people in 17 villages were told to
leave the lowlands in precaution.
</P>
<P>
According to German media reports, about 20,000 people may have
to be moved if the flood become widespread.
</P>
<P>
About 12,000 rescue workers, including nearly 9,400 soldiers
were busy in evacuating people and shoring up waterlogged dikes in
the whole flooded area on Friday. Border police and soldiers were
also patrolling villages to prevent them from lootings.
</P>
<P>
The Health Ministry of the eastern German state of Brandenburg
said there were no acute epidemic danger at the moment yet. Tap
water was still safe, but well water must be cooked to drink.
</P>
<P>
There has been no report of casualties in Germany so far, but
flooding has claimed 104 lives in neighboring Poland and the
Czech Republic over the past weeks.
</P>
<P>
The largest German reinsurance company, Muenchener
Rueckversicherung, on Friday estimated the total flood damage so
far in eastern European countries and eastern Germany at well over
one billion German marks (540 million U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
