<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drought-Hit Ethiopia Calls for Urgent Food Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 25 (Xinhua) --Ethiopia Friday appealed for
181,000 tons of food aid to be urgently sent to feed more than
three million people hit by drought in the north and south this
year.
</P>
<P>
The State Disaster Prevention and Preparedness Commission
(DPPC) said donor response to previous appeals for the aid were
very poor and the number of people hit by drought could rise,
said a report reaching here.
</P>
<P>
It said the failure of short rains from March to May known as
belg had hit some 1.4 million people in northern Amhara Region
only and other regions including Tigray and the south.
</P>
<P>
"The situation is bad in some parts of Ethiopia and the poor
belg rains will increase the need for food aid," U.N. World Food
Programme (WFP) spokeswoman Brenda Barton said in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
"There is an urgent need for food aid and WFP is finalising
its analysis of the outcome of the belg harvest," she added.
</P>
<P>
The DPPC in June estimated 3,418,190 people would need 329,451
tons of food aid this year. Aid agencies said taking into account
aid in the pipeline, there remained a shortfall of 88,753 tons of
food and the food gap was expected to widen.
</P>
<P>
U.N. missions in June to various regions reported the belg
crop was likely to be the worst in three years. The belg rains
generally started late in Ethiopia and were poor, short and
uneven.
</P>
<P>
Grain prices in Ethiopia rose by 33 percent from mid-April to
June and fertiliser sales this year by the end of June were
estimated at half what they were at the same time the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia suffered a catastrophic famine in 1984, prompting the
"live aid" rock concert which helped raise millions of dollars to
ease the disaster. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
