<HEADLINE> Angola Accuses UNITA of Violating Lusaka Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 25 (Xinhua) -- The Angolan National Assembly
today passed a resolution, accusing the National Union for the
Total Independence of Angola (UNITA), former anti-government
forces, of violating the Lusaka Peace Accord signed in November 1994.
</P>
<P>
The draft of the resolution was submitted Thursday by Angola's
ruling party, the People's Movement for the Liberation of Angola.
</P>
<P>
After nearly two days' debates, the resolution was
passed with 115 supports, 64 oppositions and 13 abstentions.
</P>
<P>
The resolution said that UNITA has trampled on the Lusaka
Peace Accord by hiding away armed personnel and war-time goods,
launching military operations against the people, sabotaging the
re-establishment of national authorities and plunging the country
once again into the danger of war.
</P>
<P>
The resolution demands that UNITA hand over all arms,
dissolve all armed personnel immediately and strictly observe
the Lusaka Peace Accord.
</P>
<P>
It also calls on UNITA Chairman Jonas Savimbi to keep his
promise by fulfilling all tasks in the peace process to make
UNITA a non-militarized party.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the resolution appeals to the international
community, the United Nations observers' mission in Angola to
take up measures to reverse the UNITA's action. 
</P>
</TEXT>
