<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 25 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from the Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- The Cypriot stock market remained flat this week
with volumes shrinking to the lowest levels for the current year.
</P>
<P>
According to a report issued by the Cyprus Investment and
Securities Corporation Limited (CISCO) today, the CISCO All-Share
Index closed Thursday at 376.7 points, virtually unaltered
since last week's closing of 376.8 points and having fluctuated
very mildly within the week.
</P>
<P>
On the very first day of trading of the current week,
activity fell to the lowest daily level of the current year
of 134,600 Cyprus pounds (about 269,200 U.S. dollars), while for
the rest of the week volumes were slightly increased but still
at extremely low levels.
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- The Cyprus Planning Bureau has predicted that the
country's economy will grow by around 3.5 percent this year as a
result of increased domestic and external demand.
</P>
<P>
In its report on economic review for 1996, released here
today, the Planning Bureau speaks of a slowdown of the Cyprus
economy in 1996 "due mainly to exogenous factors", such as the
sluggish development in European Union (EU) economies, the rise
in oil prices and the further liberalization of world trade.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Central Bank Governor Afxentis Afxentiou
expected a modest recovery of the economy this year, with real
Gross Domestic Product (GDP) rising by 2.5-3 percent, compared
with 1.9 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
But for 1997, the report says the external environment is
expected to be more favorable, with Britain's economy projected
to grow by 3 percent this year, compared with 2.3 percent in
1996. Britain is Cyprus' leading trading partner.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The Internet market in Lebanon is expanding at an
annual rate of 60 percent, a leading analyst of the local
information highway industry said today.
</P>
<P>
Mahmoud Soubra, commercial manager of Datanet, a Beirut-based
communication company, said a combination of good marketing,
better infrastructure and the Internet's worldwide appeal has
made this industry attractive in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"From the demand we have been feeling in the past six months,
60 percent is the rate of internet growth. If another analyst said
75 percent, he might not be exaggerating," Soubra said.
</P>
<P>
There are 50,000 computer users in Lebanon, and one tenth of
them have subscribed the internet, he said, adding that 55 percent
of the subscribers are businessmen, while the remaining 45 percent
are households and students.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish and Italian automobile giants Tofas and Fiat
have recently signed a 262-million-U.S. dollar contract to produce
cars for Turkish and European markets.
</P>
<P>
Local English newspaper Daily News today quoted Fiat Director
General Paoto Cantarella as saying that a new plant will be set up
in Western Turkey's coastal city of Bursa to produce the Fiat
Palio model cars.
</P>
<P>
But the report did not say when and where the contract was
signed
</P>
<P>
Cantarella said the designed capability of the project is
nearly 1 million cars per year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
