<HEADLINE> EU to Aid COMESA's Standardization Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 25 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) decided
today to provide the Common Market for Eastern and Southern
Africa (COMESA) with 2.3 million U.S. Dollars for industrial
standardization to promote international trade in the region.
</P>
<P>
At an agreement-signing ceremony, the head of EU delegation in
Zambia, Charles Brooks, urged the COMESA member countries to
eliminate technical barriers originating from different technical
standards so as to facilitate exchange of goods among trading
partners.
</P>
<P>
He said standardization of products is an essential supporting
service to sustained industrial development if products are
expected to be internationally tradable.
</P>
<P>
"To facilitate easy exchange of goods, further harmonization
of standards, quality control procedures, testing and
certification practices among the trading partners is necessary,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Acting COMESA Secretary General Erastus Mwencha said the funds
will be used in three areas of capacity building, development of
specific standards commonly traded within COMESA countries and
the dissemination of information to all stake holders.
</P>
<P>
He said that lack of standardization and multiplicity of
standards have constituted a major impediment to industrialization
in the region.
</P>
<P>
The funds will be used in addressing standards and quality of
locally produced goods which is a major non-tariff barrier to
intra-regional trade in the third world countries, Mwencha said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
