<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Women Committee Concludes 17th Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 25 (Xinhua) -- The 17th session of the
Committee of the Elimination of Discrimination against Women --
the only UN treaty body that deals exclusively with women's rights
-- concluded here today.
</P>
<P>
The 23 experts of the committee, who monitor the implementation
of the Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of
Discrimination against Women, reviewed the reports of nine states
parties to the convention during the three-week session.
</P>
<P>
The nine reports of the states parts include the initial
reports of Armenia and Namibia; the initial and second periodic
reports of Luxembourg and Israel; the combined initial, second and
third reports of Antigua and Barbuda; and the second and third
periodic reports of Argentina; the second report of Italy; the
third report of Australia; and the combined third and fourth
reports of Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
The committee adopted general recommendations covering such
issues as women's economic position; the impact of structural
adjustment policies; maternity leave; measures taken to allow
women to combine child-bearing with employment; violence against
women; the dissemination of the convention and its provisions; and
the extent to which non-governmental organizations have been
incorporated into the process of preparing reports on the
implementation of the convention.
</P>
<P>
The Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of
Discrimination against Women, which was adopted by the General
Assembly in 1979 and came into force in 1981, had been ratified by
160 countries as of June this year. It requires states parties to
eliminate discrimination against women in all areas, including
civil, political, economic and cultural rights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970726.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Attorney General Praises Arkansas Handgun Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 25 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Attorney General Janet
Reno today praised Arkansas' decision to resume background checks
under the Brady handgun act, which it had stopped doing last month
following a Supreme Court ruling that the federal government
couldn't require the checks.
</P>
<P>
Reno said that leaves only Ohio not conducting background
checks before handgun purchases.
</P>
<P>
The Brady gun-control law is named after former press secretary
James Brady, who was seriously wounded in the assassination
attempt on President Ronald Reagan. It was passed after bitter
congressional battles and was strongly opposed by the National
Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
Arkansas Attorney General Winston Bryant ruled late Thursday
that the Arkansas state police had the authority to conduct the
checks and charge a fee for them.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, Reno said that since its passage in 1994, the
Brady Act has prevented more than 250,000 fugitives, felons and
others from buying guns over the counter.
</P>
<P>
"I commend Attorney General Bryant for this step forward in
protecting the citizens of Arkansas," Reno said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
