<DOCNO> XIE19970726.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African African-American Summit Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 25 (Xinhua) -- The four-day fourth African
African-American summit concluded here this afternoon with a
declaration calling for joint efforts to promot African economic
development.
</P>
<P>
The Harare Declaration adopted at the end of the summit
stressed the objectives of the summit were to strengthen the
friendship and solidarity between Africans and African Americans
forged by history, culture and common destiny and to find the
ways and means to help accelerate the African development process
in a cooperative and consultative framework.
</P>
<P>
The declaration reaffirmed the need to intensify African
economic integration in order to identify markets for foreign
investment and industrialization.
</P>
<P>
It called on the participants to make efforts to broaden basic
education and eradicate adult illiteracy in Africa, and reduce
and write off Africa's debt to meet education and other essential
development needs.
</P>
<P>
African African-American summit with its first meeting held in
Cote d' Ivoire in 1991, is the brainchild of Leon Sullivan of the
U.S. and had over the years been a platform to strengthen
relations between Africans and African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
The Harare summit, attended by more than 2,000 delegates from
the Africa, the U.S. and Europe, provided a forum for Africans,
African- Americans and international business communities to
interact and discuss specific business, trade and investment
opportunities in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Nine African heads of state and government and the U.S.
government delegation led by former candidate for American
presidency Jesse Jackson attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
At his closing speech, Chairman of the summit and Zimbabwean
President Robert Mugabe said African leaders had shown their
seriousness in pursuing efforts to ensure peace and stability in
their countries, restructuring their economies so that they are
market driven, and espousing democracy and good governance.
</P>
<P>
He stressed, ''Cooperation, solidarity, partnership and the
goodwill of others are all very important. We have long
mentioned the need for debt forgiveness, for fairer terms of
trade, and for better treatment by international financial
institutions.''
</P>
<P>
In his address, convener of the summit Leon Sullivan urged
Africans to work to forge stronger ties for a common goal of
improving the continent's economic climate and living standards.
</P>
<P>
He also called on African Americans' companies to increase
investment in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Western governments should allow Africa to sort out its own
affairs without outside interference, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Sullivan Foundation has embarked on a number of programs
such as water and sanitation, teacher and nurse training, and
banking to help improve the living conditions of the people in
Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
