<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-26 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat: Israeli Settlement Plan Complicates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
today warned that an Israeli plan to add another Jewish settlement
on the occupied Arab lands further complicated the Middle East
situation.
</P>
<P>
"The situation undoubtedly has become complicated," Arafat told
reporters this morning after his second meeting in a week with
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak at the Mediterranean port city of
Alexandria, in an attempt to galvanize the stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
He blamed Israel's non-abidance by the signed agreements and
violations in the occupied lands for the deadlock of the peace
process. Palestinian-Israeli peace talks stalled as Israel started
in March the expansion of Jewish settlement in Har Homa, East
Jerusalem, which the Palestinians want as their future capital.
</P>
<P>
Today's Arafat-Mubarak meeting came two days after Israel's
Jerusalem City Council decided to build a Jewish settlers' enclave
in the 11,000-strong Arab neighborhood of Ras Al-Amoud in the
heart of East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Arafat blasted the Israeli decision as a scheme to "blow up"
the ongoing efforts to salvage the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"This is a new challenge to the peace process by the Israeli
Mayor of Jerusalem. He feels that there are Arab, European and
American endeavors to rescue the peace process and that is why he
is putting obstacles to hinder it," he said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has warned that such a decision, combined with the Har
Homa building, will foil ongoing peace efforts and kill the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Arafat renewed his call on the U.S. government to haul up its
flagging profile as a key sponsor and mediator of the six-year-old
peace process.
</P>
<P>
"We should not forget that we concluded peace agreements under
the sponsorship of U.S. President Bill Clinton twice in the White
House. The U.S. should shoulder its moral and political
responsibility to save the peace process and break the deadlock in
it," he added.
</P>
<P>
Under U.S. mediation, the Palestinians and Israelis struck
historic deals in Washington on the principles of realizing
Palestinian autonomy in September 1993 and on expanding autonomy
in September 1995.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. also brokered a deal on Israeli troops partial
redeployment in the West Bank city of Hebron in January this
year. But since then it has slacked off its efforts.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said his recent meetings with Israeli opposition Labor
Party leader Ehud Barak, Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy as
well as a number of European Union foreign ministers in Brussels
was part of an attempt to rescue the peace process.
</P>
<P>
But he complained the Natanyahu government deliberately foiled
the European initiative despite that it included "new factors" to
push forward the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Arafat left here for home this afternoon. An enlarged
Egyptian-Palestinian meeting will be held in Cairo on Sunday to
evaluate the present situation.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is expected to host a tripartite summit among Mubarak,
Arafat and Jordan's King Hussein by the end of this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
