<HEADLINE> Fighting Continues North of Kabul: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Fighting between the Afghan
Islamic Taliban militia and their rivals was continuing today
north of the capital city of Kabul, Pakistan Television (PTV) said
today.
</P>
<P>
For the past two days there had been no significant change in
the frontlines which were reported to be still around Hossein Kot
village, about 20 kilometers north of Kabul, PTV said.
</P>
<P>
However, there was no clear indication today that the
anti-Taliban forces, under the commander of Ahmad Masood, the
Afghan former military chief, would attempt to storm the capital.
</P>
<P>
The Masood's forces, which have advanced to within the rocket
range of Kabul, have kept military pressure on the city with jet
and artillery bombardments while calling for a Taliban pullout
from the capital.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued today by the United Islamic Front for the
Salvation of Afghanistan (UIFSA), the name of the anti-Taliban
alliance, said that only when the Taliban "demilitarize Kabul"
could issues including a cease-fire and exchange of prisoners be
negotiated. But it gave no deadline for the demilitarization of
Kabul.
</P>
<P>
The atmosphere in Kabul remained tense as the Taliban rushed in
reinforcements and reportedly arrested hundreds of people
suspected to be opposition fighters who were said to have
infiltrated the capital.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of foreign aid workers evacuated by road to the
Pakistani border Friday as the anti-Taliban forces were poised to
close in on Kabul. The United Nations and the International
Committee of the Red Cross have also suspended their flights to
the city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
