<HEADLINE> Stone Column Marking HK's Return to China Unveiled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 26 (Xinhua) -- A stone column marking Hong
Kong's return to China on July 1 this year was unveiled today at
Sheung Tsuen Park, Yuen Long of the "New Territories".
</P>
<P>
Nearly 2,000 people attended the unveiling ceremony for the
11.6-meter-high column, whose construction was funded by the Pat
Heung Rural Committee and began on May 13.
</P>
<P>
A dozen noted figures of the local community, including vice
director of the Xinhua News Agency Hong Kong Branch Zheng Guoxiong
and chairwoman of the Provisional Legislative Council of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region Rita Fan Hsu Lai Tai, cut the
ribbon for the occasion.
</P>
<P>
Engraved on the front of the column was an inscription by Zhou
Nan, former director of the Xinhua Hong Kong Branch, which reads
"Sky-sustaining pillar in commemoration of Hong Kong's return".
</P>
<P>
Philip Lai, chairman of the Pat Heung Rural Committee, said
that members of the committee donated more than one million Hong
Kong dollars (about 128,000 US dollars) for the erection of the
column.
</P>
<P>
With 26 villages and a population of over 20,000, Pat Heung is
known for its resistance against the British aggression in the
1890s, when more than 40 local residents sacrificed their lives in
an attempt to defend the area against British occupation.
</P>
<P>
"The people of Pat Heung have a tradition of patriotism, and we
are ecstatic about Hong Kong's return to the motherland," said
Lai.
</P>
<P>
Participants at today's ceremony, mostly from the nearby
villages, celebrated the occasion with a deafening sound of gongs
and drums, lion and dragon dances and a grand open-air
feast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
