<HEADLINE> HKAAA Applying for Suspended Woman Hurdler to Appeal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 26 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Amateur Athletic
Association (HKAAA) is now applying for its top woman hurdler Chan
Sau Ying to appeal to the International Amateur Athletic
Federation (IAAF) against her suspension from all competitions.
</P>
<P>
Chan, 26, was tested positive of ephedrine during the Zagreb
'97 EAA Meeting in Zagreb, Croatia, on June 27 this year and was
thus suspended by the world government body for track and field
for three months. The suspension started from June 27.
</P>
<P>
She was the first ever Hong Kong athlete to be suspended for
failing doping tests during international competitions.
</P>
<P>
In a press release issued here today, the HKAAA said that it
"views this matter with grave concern and every effort has been
made to rectify the matter."
</P>
<P>
HKAAA Chairman William Ko has decided to fly to Athens on
Sunday to discuss the issue with IAAF anti-doping officials. He
would ask for sample test reports, which he would send back to
Hong Kong for medical advice.
</P>
<P>
The Association has prepared a Notice of Application for Chan
Sau Ying to file in for hearing as in accordance with the IAAF
rules. The Notice of Application must reach the IAAF within 28
days.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the HKAAA believed that Chan had taken drugs by
mistake.
</P>
<P>
Chan herself is not available now for comment.
</P>
<P>
The IAAF said that it's not up to the IAAF to ban the hurdler
and it is the responsibility of HKAAA to conduct a thorough
investigation and make any decision on her.
</P>
<P>
Chan won a silver medal in the 100 meters hurdles at the East
Asian Games in Pusan, South Korea in May and took a gold in an
international meeting in Belgium on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Local TV reports today said that the HKAAA had decided to
suspend bonus money awarded to Chan and erase her name from the
team for next month's world championships.
</P>
<P>
And Chan might not be eligible for China's Eighth National
Games in October in Shanghai.  
</P>
</TEXT>
