<HEADLINE> Iraq Willing to Normalize Ties with Arab Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Nabeel Najim, Iraq's permanent
representative to the Arab League, has said that his country is
willing to normalize ties with all other Arab states, according to
the Iraqi News Agency today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with an Egyptian newspaper, Najim underlined
that his country is ready to do so even with those it has been at
odds, and to turn over a new leaf in their bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
He said Iraq is in dire need for developing relations with
other Arab countries before the advent of the coming century in
light of the economic, social, cultural, and media challenges it
faces.
</P>
<P>
This is aimed at establishing sound inter-Arab relations which
will benefit the pan-Arab security, he said.
</P>
<P>
Najim added that what happened in the past could not deny the
existence of an "objective" vision of the present and future.
</P>
<P>
Most of the Arab countries cut off their official exchanges
with Iraq after it invaded Kuwait in August, 1990. Nine of them
joined in the U.S.-led military operations or provided facilities
in the 1991 Gulf War that evicted Iraqi troops out of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Najim urged the United Nations to lift its seven-year-old
sanctions against Iraq, which was imposed after the Gulf War
banning the sale of Iraqi oil for purposes other than food and
medicine.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.N. oil-for-food deal does not meet the
humanitarian needs of the Iraqi people as more than 53 percent of
the food and medicine supply Iraq contracted has yet to arrive.
</P>
<P>
In his statement, Najim also criticized Turkey's alliance with
Israel, the long-term foe of many Arab countries. He said the
alliance would "negatively" affect the Arab national security.
</P>
<P>
He called for mapping out an Arab strategy to protect the
security of the Arab nations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
