<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China "Deeply Concerned" Over Cambodian Situation-Qian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PETALING JAYA, Malaysia, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Chinese
Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen today expressed his
country's concern over the situation in Cambodia and urged the
sides involved in the fighting there to solve their problems
peacefully.
</P>
<P>
"China is deeply concerned over what has recently taken place
in Cambodia," Qian, who is here to attend the ASEAN Regional Forum
and Post Ministerial Conference, told a press conference he
jointly held with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
China does not wish to see the eruption of armed conflict in
Cambodia, which had already achieved national reconciliation and
established a coalition government, he said.
</P>
<P>
Qian expressed the hope that Cambodian parties and leaders
would solve their problems and disagreements through peaceful
means.
</P>
<P>
"Our consistent position is not to interfere in other
countries' internal affairs, but we wish to see that they will be
able to work out their problems by peaceful means," he declared.
</P>
<P>
On Chinese President Jiang Zemin's planned visit to the United
States this fall, the vice-premier said the purpose of the trip
will be the establishment of a strategic partnership between the
two countries that is oriented toward the 21st century, as the
Chinese president told U.S. President Bill Clinton at their first
meeting in 1994.
</P>
<P>
"China and the United States are both major countries," he
said. "We will exchange views on the international situation and
on global issues and this makes our relationship strategic."
</P>
<P>
"The upcoming visit should be more than just of protocol
significance, it should have substantive significance. In other
words, it should generate concrete results."
</P>
<P>
He said China and the United States do not agree on everything,
but it is possible for the two countries to reach agreement and
achieve results on major issues.
</P>
<P>
On the human rights issue, Qian noted that China stands for
dialogue and wants to avoid confrontation.
</P>
<P>
He called for holding such dialogue on a forum such as a
non-governmental organization forum and the topics for discussion
could cover issues such as human rights and the exchange of
judicial experience.
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed that "All such discussions must be based
on mutual respect and non-interference in each other's internal
affairs." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
