<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, New Zealand to Strengthen Economic Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PETALING JAYA, MALAYSIA, July 26 (Xinhua) -- China and New
Zealand today agreed to further strengthen their bilateral
economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached at the talks here today between
Chinese Foreign Minister Qian Qichen and his New Zealand
counterpart Don Mckinnon, a spokesman for the Chinese foreign
ministry said at a news briefing.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers shared the view that there exist great
potentials for the two countries to have mutually beneficial
economic and trade cooperation as the two countries have great
economic complementarity.
</P>
<P>
They were satisfied with the "smooth development of bilateral
relations between the two countries," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Qian said the Chinese government attaches great importance to
its relations with New Zealand and wishes to work together with it
to deepen the cooperation and contacts existing in various fields.
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand minister said it is also his country's desire
to do so, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Mckinnon believed that an early solution to the issue of
China's entry into the World Trade Organization would further
promote the economic and trade relations between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers also discussed some regional issues, the
spokesman said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
