<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-26 12:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese, Western Firms Vie for UAE Gas Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 26 ( Xinhua) -- Japanese and Western firms are
vying to snatch a major UAE gas project which will tap the Gulf
country's immense resources, a local newspaper said here today.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Dhabi National Oil Company (Adnoc), which runs the
energy sector, has invited bids for the 1 billion U.S. dollars
project to develop Habshan field, one of the largest oil fields in
the Middle East, the daily Gulf news said.
</P>
<P>
Technip of France, Bechtel and Fluor Corp. of the United
States, Mitsubishi and Chiyoda of Japan, and other companies
are competing for the contract.
</P>
<P>
The project will turn Habshan field located in the west of UAE,
into one of the biggest single point gas processing plants with a
total treating capacity of around 90 million cubic meters a day.
</P>
<P>
Abu Dhabi approved the ambitious Onshore Gas Development in
1991 to exploit its largely untapped reserves of natural gas.
</P>
<P>
The gas resources of the UAE are estimated at around 5.7
trillion cubic meters, the fourth largest in the world after the
reserves of Russia, Iran and Qatar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
