<DOCNO> XIE19970726.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign-Funded Enterprises Successful in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Recent statistics show that the
industrial output value of foreign-funded enterprises in China's
largest trade and financial city has grown to account for over one
third of the city's total.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the Shanghai Statistics Bureau say that the number
of foreign-funded enterprises in Shanghai has increased to 4,020
since the city's first foreign firm, the Shanghai Schindler
Elevator Co., Ltd, was built in 1980.
</P>
<P>
The figure is still increasing, official sources say.
</P>
<P>
The total industrial output of the enterprises was 170 billion
yuan last year, accounting for 34.4 percent of the city's total.
</P>
<P>
The sources say that their output value has increased at an
average annual growth rate of 72 percent since 1980, with their
tax and profits hitting 16.9 billion yuan in 1996, growing at a
rate of 60.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The ventures have employed nearly 588,000 local residents, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
After years of expanding, overseas investors have penetrated
into each sector of the local industrial economy. However, most of
them are involved in textiles, electronics, telecommunications,
foodstuffs and chemical industries, they said.
</P>
<P>
The tax and profits made by the Shanghai Volkswagon Corporation
increased to 4.5 billion yuan in 1996, making the company the
leader among foreign-funded enterprises in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Industrial specialists say that overseas investors have brought
advanced technology and skills into the city, which helps push the
city's production technology toward world standards.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai had approved 16,420 foreign-funded enterprises by the
end of June, with a total registered capital of 44 billion US
dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
