<DOCNO> XIE19970726.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Britain Working in Cooperation for Pollution Control Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, July 26 (Xinhua) -- A Sino-British cooperative project
to improve pollution-control efforts in the Yangpu Economic
Development Zone is progressing smoothly in Haikou, capital of
China's southernmost Hainan Province.
</P>
<P>
Yangpu is China's first economic development zone to allow
overseas investors to lease large tracts of land from the local
government. The zone will be built into a chemical industrial base
to refine offshore oil and gases.
</P>
<P>
The pollution-control project is mainly sponsored by the
British Overseas Development Agency (ODA), and covers three
Chinese coastal cities, Fuzhou and Quanzhou in Fujian Province in
the east, and Haikou.
</P>
<P>
The ODA provided 1.67 million US dollars (one million British
pounds) to finance the work, which will cost a total 2.167 million
US dollars (1.3 million British pounds).
</P>
<P>
British experts in environmental protection have formed a team
together with Chinese consultants and experts to develop a
anti-pollution program for Yangpu.
</P>
<P>
The largest chemical fertilizer plant in Asia will go under
construction in Yangpu at the end of this year. The facility is
expected to have an annual production capacity of 450,000 tons of
synthetic ammonia, and 800,000 tons of urea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
