<HEADLINE> Computer Literacy Craze in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Lu Liuying, a 40-year-old
employee of the Shanghai municipal government, recently became the
one millionth person to pass a computer science examination in
China's largest city.
</P>
<P>
Computer literacy has become a new craze in Shanghai: there are
now about 600,000 people like Lu who have received course
completion certificates for computer science. Statistics show that
one out of every 13 Shanghai residents has taken a test in
computer studies.
</P>
<P>
In the autumn of 1993, the Shanghai municipal government
started a "Personnel Training Project" and computer science was
one of its basic courses.
</P>
<P>
Since then, about two million books on computer science have
been published, and one million handbooks for computer use.
</P>
<P>
To help its computer students, the Shanghai computer testing
center has offered new software to be used in conjunction with the
courses.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai currently has 420 schools for computer training, and
about 120 classrooms are opened for every exam.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that about 20 percent of families in Shanghai
owns a computer.  
</P>
</TEXT>
