<DOCNO> XIE19970726.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1,300-year-old Stone Buddha Found in Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, July 26 (Xinhua) -- A 1,300-year-old stone Buddha was
discovered recently, which was carved into the face of a perilous
part of Hengshan, a mountainous Buddhist shrine in central China's
Hunan province.
</P>
<P>
The two-meter-tall stone carving is a bit indistinct after
hundreds of years of wind and rain. Local experts believe that it
is the image of Sakyamuni, the founder of Buddhism.
</P>
<P>
Nothing else was reported near it, but four Chinese characters
are carved on a huge rock nearby.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists say that the figure belongs to the early Tang
Dynasty (618-907) because of the style.
</P>
<P>
Master Bao Tan, the Buddhist abbot of Nantai Temple and
vice-president of the provincial Buddhism association, believes
that the carving was the work of local craftsmen acting on their
own instead of on government order, because there is no record in
local chronicles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
