<DOCNO> XIE19970726.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Expects Constructive Relationship With China, Albright </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PETALING JAYA, MALAYSIA, July 26 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of
State Madeline Albright said here today the United States is aimed
at building the basis for a sound and constructive relationship
with China.
</P>
<P>
At a joint press conference with Chinese Vice-Premier and
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen, Albright said her meeting with Qian
today will be the fourth of its kind over the past six months,
which showed that "both our countries have attached great
importance to our relationship."
</P>
<P>
She said the United States views its relations with China as a
major relationship as it enters the next century.
</P>
<P>
She expressed her appreciation of the dialogue between the two
countries which is proceeding "with great seriousness," and "is
producing tangible, fair and growing benefits."
</P>
<P>
By the summit between U.S. President Bill Clinton and his
Chinese counterpart Jiang Zemin scheduled for this fall, the two
sides would work to increase cooperation in the areas "where we
share the same interests and the same goals" and try to narrow the
differences between the two, Albright said.
</P>
<P>
She said Qian and she would discuss the situation in Cambodia
and the issue of the Korean Peninsula at today's meeting.
</P>
<P>
She said the United States is also ready to deepen the
cooperation with China on global issues including energy,
environment, law enforcement and nuclear non-proliferation.
</P>
<P>
"We certainly do not agree on everything, but I do think we do
agree that the important test of the relationship we are building
will be our ability to produce appropriate results in these and
other areas," she said.
</P>
<P>
"As we move forward, I know that we can continue to resolve
differences, expand cooperation and build understanding and I
anticipate that the larger and longer process of deepening ties
between our nations will produce greater benefits for both
countries," she added.
</P>
<P>
Albright said she hoped that Jiang's upcoming state visit to
her country would show the bilateral ties between the two are
increasingly profound and useful to both countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
