<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Kant Nominated Candidate for Vice President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 26 (Xinhua) -- India's ruling United Front and
the Congress party today unanimously nominated Krishan Kant,
governor of the southern state Andhra Pradesh, as their joint
candidate for the post of vice president.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made at a joint press conference by Prime
Minister Inder Kumar Gujral, Congress party President Sitaram
Kesri and other leaders of the United Front at the prime
minister's residence here today.
</P>
<P>
The United Front parties and the Congress party, which supports
the United Front government from outside, will jointly file
nomination papers for Kant on Monday, Gujral told the press
conference.
</P>
<P>
An activist in India's freedom movement during British rule,
Kant had been imprisoned along with his family by the British.
</P>
<P>
Kesri described Kant as an honest, sincere and able
administrator who had sacrificed a lot during the freedom
struggle.
</P>
<P>
Gujral said he hoped the opposition parties would support the
candidature of Kant, known for his "impeccable integrity" and wide
experience in public life and administration.
</P>
<P>
Kant, 70, is a scientist, a prolific writer, and a member of
parliament.
</P>
<P>
The election for vice president is scheduled to be held on
August 16. 
</P>
</TEXT>
