<HEADLINE> Israeli Forces Bombard South Lebanese Villages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Israeli occupation forces
bombarded this morning villages opposite the Israeli
self-proclaimed "security zone" in south Lebanon, wounding one
civilian, security sources in the area said.
</P>
<P>
In the fiercest bombardment in one week apparent retaliatory
against Katyusha attacks on Israeli positions in the buffer area,
Israeli forces fired more than 50 heavy shells, wounding a
60-year-old woman at Sohmour in Western Beqaa.
</P>
<P>
This constituted a breach of a cease-fire understanding Lebanon
and Israel reached in April, 1996 barring either side in south
Lebanon from targeting civilians, accused the sources who
preferred anonymity.
</P>
<P>
A position of the Israeli occupation forces at Ghzlan and
another of the Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army (SLA) militia at
Sojoud were shelled by Katyusha rockets earlier this morning,
said Voice of the South radio, organ of the SLA militia. It denied
any casualties.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God, claimed
responsibility for the attacks, and announced that "certain
casualties among the Israeli occupation forces and their client
militia were caused."
</P>
<P>
This was the second Katyusha attack in two weeks by the Shiite
Muslim group at Israeli targets in south Lebanon. Katyusha is
believed to the longest-range weapon of Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah also announced that its guerrillas carried out this
morning attacks on the Israeli positions of Rshaf and Hommeid in
the border strip with rocket-propelled grenades and machine-guns.
</P>
<P>
However, today's violence did not go beyond daily exchanges of
fire on the last active battlefront of the Arab-Isreali conflict,
where Hezbollah spearheads a guerrilla warfare to oust the Israeli
occupation forces out of the Lebanese land.
</P>
<P>
Israel proclaimed the 1,100-square-kilometer "security zone" in
south Lebanon in 1985 ostensibly to insinuate northern Israel
from cross-border attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
