<HEADLINE> China, U.S. Pledge to Promote Ties to New High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PETALING JAYA, MALAYSIA, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-
Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen and U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright met here today and pledged to promote
relations between China and the United States to a new high.
</P>
<P>
The two countries should "look at and treat the bilateral
relations with a long-term strategic view, uphold the common
interests of the two sides, make efforts to build up consensus and
strengthen cooperation, as well as solve the differences and
problems in a proper way," Qian and Albright said at a news
briefing after their talks.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders are here to attend the Regional Forum and Post
Ministerial Conference of the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN), which begins tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed that relationship between China and the
U.S. has improved in recent years, and the scheduled state visit
by Chinese President Jiang Zemin this fall to the U.S. is of great
importance to the establishment of strategic partnership between
the two countries, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He added that both Qian and Albright expressed their
satisfaction over the preparations so far made for the visit.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also exchanged views on international and
regional issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
They shared the view that it is important for China and the
U.S., both as permanent members of the U.N. Security Council, to
conduct strategic dialogue and strengthen cooperation on
international and regional issues.
</P>
<P>
They stressed that peace and stability in the Asia-Pacific
region should be maintained and differences and disputes in the
region solved through peaceful means.  
</P>
