<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Build 40 Billion Yuan Hydropower Project in '98 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, July 26 (Xinhua) -- China is preparing to build a
gigantic hydropower plant for an estimated 40 billion yuan (about
five billion US dollars), with construction scheduled to begin
next year, according to sources from Three Gorges Engineering
Development Corporation, owner of the Three Gorges Project.
</P>
<P>
The new Xiluodu Project, to be located in the upper reaches of
the Jinsha River in southwest China's Sichuan Province, is
designed to have an installed capacity of 11 million kw which can
generate 52.6 billion kwh of electricity a year.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that the installed capacity of the project is
three times more than that of the Gezhouba Project on the Yangtze
River, while the construction scale is about two-thirds the size
of the Three Gorges, China's largest power project.
</P>
<P>
The project is considered one of the key steps adopted by the
government to tap into the rich hydraulic resources along the
Yangtze River. Also, the construction site is located in China's
less populous region, and thus the cost of construction will be
much lower than elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
Upon completion of this project, the power generation
capacities of the Sanxia (three-gorges) Power Plant and Gezhouba
Project can provide an additional 800,000 kw, thus allowing
provinces in southwest China to save 24 million tons of fuel from
coal and oil.
</P>
<P>
The electricity is set to be transmitted eastward to support
the economic construction in the electricity-poor east regions.
</P>
</TEXT>
