<HEADLINE> Taliban Arrest Hundreds in Kabul-Reports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 26 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Islamic Taliban
militia have reportedly arrested hundreds of people suspected to
be the opposition fighters, reports monitored here said today.
</P>
<P>
These people were arrested as the Taliban forces tried to
tighten the security around the streets in the capital Kabul, the
reports said.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, who have occupied the Afghan capital since last
September, have stepped up the search of all passing vehicles
after reports said the opposition forces had infiltrated various
parts of the capital.
</P>
<P>
The anti-Taliban forces, which have advanced to within the
rocket range of Kabul, have kept military pressure on Kabul with
jet and artillery bombardments while urging the Taliban to
demilitarize the capital.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued today by the United Islamic Front for the
Salvation of Afghanistan (UIFSA) said that only when the Taliban
"demilitarize Kabul" could issues including a cease-fire and
exchange of prisoners be negotiated.
</P>
<P>
The UIFSA was created on June 2 to replace the previous
opposition Council for Defense of Afghanistan under ousted Uzbek
warlord Rashid Dostum, who fled the country after his right-hand
man Abdul Malik revolted against him on May 19.
</P>
<P>
The renamed anti-Taliban alliance are made up mainly of the
forces led by Malik, former Afghan military chief Ahmad Masood and
the Shiite Hezb-e-Wahdat.  
</P>
</TEXT>
