<HEADLINE> South Chinese Region's Port Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, July 26 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region will spend 670 million yuan on two 10,000-dwt
berths at Fangcheng port.
</P>
<P>
Construction work on the berths, which are expected to have a
handling capacity of 2.64 million tons annually, is scheduled to
start next month.
</P>
<P>
Fangcheng Port was built in 1968 and has now had 25 berths, 10
of which can accommodate 10,000-dwt ships. It is one of the
country's 19 major ports, handling a wide range of foodstuff, bulk
cargo, containers, and transit business. It opened to the outside
world in 1983 and has contacts with 159 ports in 64 countries and
regions.
</P>
<P>
Fangcheng handled more than three million tons of goods during
the first half of this year, a 28 percent rise from the same
period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The port improvements and a new highway linking it to nearby
Qinzhou city are expected to increase its capacity a great
deal.  
</P>
</TEXT>
