<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Succeeds in Ancient Grotto Moving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Chinese relics experts have for
the first time successfully moved a 1,400-year-old grotto, slated
to be submerged in a reservoir now under construction on the
Yellow River, to a spot 50 km away, where it will be used as a
museum.
</P>
<P>
The grotto was located 10 m above the water among steep
cliffs. For the past several hundred years, few people have been
able to get to it to see it, local residents say.
</P>
<P>
The grotto, lying 40 km west of Yin'an County, central China's
Henan Province, was built between 525 and 531. More than 200
Buddha carvings and four relief sculptures of pagodas were found
in its caves.
</P>
<P>
In order to save the grotto from submersion, experts received
approval from the State Bureau of Cultural Relics to work out a
detailed plan to move it.
</P>
<P>
Before cutting the grotto out of the cliff, the experts copied
all the items inside the caves to ensure they will reappear in
their original form when the grotto reaches its final
destination.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970726.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Abacha Explains Nigeria's Presence in Sierra </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's head of state General
Sani Abacha yesterday explained why his military government is
sending troops to Sierra Leone to fight against a military
takeover there.
</P>
<P>
He said the west African peace-keeping force (ECOMOG) led by
Nigeria in Sierra Leone is not there to intervene in the internal
affairs of that country, because ECOMOG is a peace force, not a
warring one.
</P>
<P>
"We are in Sierra Leone because we have a mandate which is in
the national security interest of the Sierra Leonean people and
the entire sub-region," he said.
</P>
<P>
"ECOMOG is in Sierra Leone to secure and defend the democratic
interests and values of that country," he added.
</P>
<P>
Abacha emphasized that the effort in Sierra Leone is a
sub-regional effort under the auspices of the Economic Community
of West African States (ECOWAS). Nigeria believes in collectivity
as the right approach to security and development, he said.
</P>
<P>
If it appeared that Nigeria's presence in Sierra Leone is
conspicuous, he said, it is because of her leading role and
commitment to ECOWAS, especially to the ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
As he is currently the chairman of ECOWAS, Abacha said Nigeria
will continue to work hard for the security and stability in west
Africa, and that it will continue to provide leadership in any
significant development in the sub-region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
