<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-26 12:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan to Invite Observers to Oversee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Jordan has decided to invite
international observers to oversee the parliamentary elections
scheduled for November 4 to defuse the uproar from six political
parties to boycott them, local Arabic Expression Daily reported
today.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the invitation of international observers, the
government would also like to settle the disputes with the
political parties on the upcoming elections through dialog,
Jordanian Minister of Interior Nathir Rasheed was quoted as saying
in an interview with the paper.
</P>
<P>
The move came after Jordanian King Hussein Wednesday issued a
royal decree ordering the go-ahead for the elections, while six
political parties have declared to boycott them.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the Muslim Brotherhood, a main opposition
party, became the first to declare to boycott the elections.
</P>
<P>
The opposition party's general supervisor Abdul Majeed
Thneibat said on July 12 that the Press and Publication Law,
the one-person, one-vote election system, the normalization of
ties with Israel and "the government's measures to marginalize
political parties" were the main reasons behind the party`s
boycott of the elections.
</P>
<P>
On July 20, four other political parties, including the Jordan
People`s Democratic Party, the Jordan Arab Constitutional Front,
the National Action Front and the Al Ansar, followed suit.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic Action Front (IAF), the biggest opposition party
in Jordan, also declared to boycott the elections Friday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some other political parties also showed support for
the boycott, but have not declared whether they will boycott or
not.
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties now make up 23 seats in the 80-member
Lower House of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
Multi-party system was revived in the country in 1989 as part
of the political reforms launched after widespread riots set
off by economic hardships. The protesters called for wider
public participation in decision-making. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
