<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Disabled Man Helps Educate Poor Rural Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, July 26 (Xinhua) -- A disabled young man in a
poverty-stricken area in North China has begun a program to help
school dropouts with his own private school.
</P>
<P>
Liu Weichang, who lives in Puzhai Village in Hebei Province,
says that he is sticking to his principle of helping, not
profiting from, poor rural children, with his 'Dawn' school.
</P>
<P>
The 31-year-old man survived polio in childhood and went on to
complete primary and secondary school. Refusing to stop there, he
passed the entrance exam for the Central Academy of Finance's
correspondence school.
</P>
<P>
After completing his higher education in 1991, Liu made up his
mind to set up the primary school in his village, which is in an
impoverished area.
</P>
<P>
The next year, 12 of his pupils managed to enter middle
schools, including seven who were able to attend the county's key
middle school.
</P>
<P>
Word of the drab three-room school spread, and with that its
popularity grew, but its annual tuition fee stayed at 200 yuan (24
US dollars) or below. And in fact, Liu exempted six extremely poor
pupils from any school fees at all.
</P>
<P>
By now, Liu can boast of a new schoolhouse and a dormitory on a
hectare of land, thanks to a bank loan. And, his teaching staff
have grown from one single teacher to 24. 
</P>
</TEXT>
