<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Construction Brings Rent Tumbling in Kampala </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 26 (Xinhua) -- A steady growth in the
construction industry in Kampala has caused an evident decrease
of rent for business space or a office, The Monitor reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Comparing to early 1990s, the rent rate in the city has fallen
by ten percent, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
In a survey carried out in June and July in the main
commercial area of Kampala, the newspaper found a month rent for
a square meter of office space is between 3,000 to 20,000 Uganda
shillings according to the location and the state of the
buildings while in early 1990s it was 5,000 to 30,000 Uganda
shillings (some 1,000 Uganda shillings are equivelent to one U.S.
dollar).
</P>
<P>
The estates experts the paper interviewed with attributed the
fall of the rent to returning of Asian businessmen who renovated
their buildings and the construction of new shopping and office
blocks.
</P>
<P>
Michael Baligwa, a letting agent, told the paper that the rent
charges were much higher a year before due to minimal available
space to let.
</P>
<P>
Reduced number of clients like embassies and non-government
organisations in Kampala is another reason of the tumbling, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Stephen Kituuka, a private land economist and valuation
surveyor, holds the rent falling is connected to the rapidly
increasing of buildings. "this is going to be a steady trend in
the future," he concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
