<DOCNO> XIE19970726.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeast Chinese Province Developing Food Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, July 26 (Xinhua) -- China's Jilin Province plans to
turn the food industry into its third major one, after automobiles
and petroleum, by the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
Food businesses at or above the county level are expected to
generate 25 billion yuan (3 billion US dollars) in annual output
value by the year 2000, accounting for nearly one fifth of the
industrial total.
</P>
<P>
A traditional high-yield agricultural province, Jilin heads the
country in per capita grain consumption, volume of marketable
grains, and corn exports. The province produces about 15 million
tons of corn a year, accounting for 70 percent of the province's
total.
</P>
<P>
Its food industry has 12.5 billion yuan (1.51 billion US
dollars) in output value and earns more than 300 million US
dollars in foreign exchange from exports yearly. But it focuses on
primary processing and fails to provide a variety of goods.
</P>
<P>
So, Jilin province will give priority to processing of local
grain and livestock. It has the largest corn- and
starch-processing plants in the country, which can process over a
million tons of corn and produce 240,000 tons of starch a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
