<HEADLINE> S. African Residential Property Industry Remains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Foreign investors are
spending a huge amount of money on residential properties for
profit in South Africa, despite the rising crime rate in the
country.
</P>
<P>
According to a random survey of a few Johannesburg estate
agents and property executives this week, wealthy foreign
businessmen and investors recently have invested more than one
billion Rand (226 million U.S. Dollars) in property in the
Johannesburg region.
</P>
<P>
A steady stream of upmarket house-hunters from Malaysia, the
United States, Germany, Holland and Portugal are flying to
Johannesburg to look at properties, Melrose Estate agent Wendy
Machanik said early this week.
</P>
<P>
"South Africa properties are the cheapest in the world and
these buyers are not only interested in investing but also in
living here.
</P>
<P>
"They take a long-term view about the crime situation and
believe it will eventually be brought under control," Machanik
said.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that total foreign investment in South Africa
had amounted to 12.3 billion Rand (2.73 billion U.S. Dollars) in
equity on the Johannesburg Stock Exchange this year with under
five billion Rand (1.1 billion U.S. Dollars) for 1996.
</P>
<P>
Local property industrialists expressed belief that strong
demand for residential property in South Africa will continue for
years, providing the country remains stable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
