<HEADLINE> HKSAR Government Asks Banks to Help Repair Old Buildings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 26 (Xinhua) -- The government of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) has asked banks to consider
special loans and mortgages for property owners to repair old
buildings in the region, the Hong Kong Standard newspaper reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Under a proposed mandatory building safety inspection scheme
worked out by the government recently, owners of the 25,000
buildings that are 20 years old or over would be required to
employ building professionals to inspect their property once every
 seven years, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
As some property owners said they could not afford the
expensive inspection and the repair bills and their buildings were
too old for extra mortgage from banks, the paper quoted a
government spokesman as saying the government understood that some
of these owners had difficulties getting bank loans.
</P>
<P>
"We want to see if any help could be given by the banks to
those owners," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Standard continued, top housing managers in the
Hong Kong SAR called on the government to help resume land for
private developers to speed up the building of flats.
</P>
<P>
Fan Cheuk-hung, professional practice committee chairman of the
1,300-strong Chartered Institute of Housing, said the government
should introduce new measures to help private developers in
resuming land for its massive housing program, the daily added.
</P>
</TEXT>
