<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Kenya Committed to Control Oil prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 26 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government may impose
price control measures in the oil industry to enable consumers to
benefit from a liberalized petroleum sector.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Energy Minister Kirugi M'Mukindia was quoted as saying
on Friday that the current deregulation regime had empowered the
government to fix maximum prices of petroleum products if deemed
necessary.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with senior executives of oil companies, the
minister noted that the government was concerned that Kenyans had
not been able to reap the benefit of liberalization of the oil
industry.
</P>
<P>
Since the liberalization of the oil sector in October 1994,
the retail price of the liquified petroleum gas (LPG) has doubled
while the cost of refining crude oil has gone up by 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan official viewed the situation as constituting total
exploitation of the local consumers and urged oil companies to
take necessary actions to reduce the price of LPG.
</P>
<P>
M'Mukindia announced that his ministry was committed to the
introduction of standardization of cylinder valves and regulators
for the LPG.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that oil companies in the country had resisted
the standardization in order to exploit the Kenyan consumers.
</P>
<P>
The minister disclosed that the government would introduce the
open tender system in the procurement of the country's crude oil
requirements in a bid to get oil at the cheapest prices.
</P>
<P>
At present, seven multi-national oil companies operating in
the east African country have formed cartels to monopolize the
local oil markets, charging unreasonable prices and driving
smaller firms out of the market.
</P>
<P>
In order to rout out monopolistic tendencies, the Kenyan
government has licensed 13 private oil companies to compete with
the giant companies.
</P>
<P>
The state-owned National Oil Corporation of Kenya and the
Kenya Pipeline Company are investing in service stations,
liquified petroleum gas import terminal and other facilities to
provide alternative services to local consumers.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government is also considering to take legal
measures to neutralize cartel and monopolistic practices in the
energy sector for the benefit of consumers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970726.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Ruling Coalition Keeps out Breakaway Faction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 26 (Xinhua) -- The leadership of India's ruling
United Front has decided to keep the Rashtriya Janata Party (RJD)
out of the coalition government, bringing to an end weeks of
internal bickering over the status of the breakaway faction, the
local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
After a three-hour marathon meeting late Friday night, the
Standing Committee of the United Front decided to shut the door on
RJD.
</P>
<P>
Laloo Prasad Yadav, former Janata Dal president and Bihar chief
minister, floated the RJD on July 5 following a fierce power
struggle within the Janata Dal, the largest party in the United
Front before the split.
</P>
<P>
Yadav's opponents in the United Front, including former Prime
Minister H.D. Deve Gowda, the truncated Janata Dal and left
parties, have been strongly opposing the entry of the RJD into the
coalition, and they have been pressing Prime Minister Inder Kumar
Gujral to remove his three ministers nominated by Yadav.
</P>
<P>
They argued that because Yadav was facing corruption charges
for his alleged involvement in an embezzlement scandal, the clean
image of the coalition would be tainted by the entry of his RJD.
</P>
<P>
Some other factions of the front, such as the Dravida Munnetra
Kazhagam (DMK), favored the staying of RJD in the front and the
three ministers loyal to Yadav in the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The disputes focusing on the fate of the RJD and three
Yadav-nominated ministers had posed serious threats to the
stability of the three-month-old Gujral coalition.
</P>
<P>
As a compromise, the United Front leaders did not take a
decision on the fate of the three ministers but left it to Prime
Minister Gujral's discretion. Gujral has publicly favored the
continued staying of the three ministers in his government.
</P>
<P>
Also on Friday, just hours before the United Front leaders
decided to keep out the RJD, Yadav announced his decision to
resign as chief minister of Bihar state after a special court of
the Central Bureau of Investigation had issued an arrest warrant
against him on corruption charges.
</P>
<P>
But Yadav managed to install his wife as new chief minister of
the state hours after his resignation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
