<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 26 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is trying to stop
a new project to build a Jewish settlement in the full heart of
the Muslim district of Jerusalem. The project, planned by the
Jerusalem municipality without consulting Netanyahu, could trigger
a new round of violence between Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
-- The list of dead accounts published by Swiss banks this week
mixed victims with butchers. The 1,872 owners of dead accounts,
which contain many Jews who were killed in Nazi death camps, also
include Heinrich Hofmann, the personal photographer of Hitler,
former Slovak Prime Minister Vojech Tuka who was held responsible
for the deportation of 107,000 Jews, Herman Esser, former
vice-president of the German parliament, Herman Schmitz, president
of a factory enslaving inmates of death camps, and Karl Jager, who
participated in exterminating Jews in Lithuania.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin reaffirmed on Friday
that the aim of his budgetary policy next year is not to surpass
the three-percent-criteria set by the Maastricht treaty. During an
interview with Radio-Television Luxembourg, Jospin said that if
one wants to reform the state for improving budgetary situation,
he has to make some "bad choices."
</P>
<P>
-- French President Jacques Chirac made a visit to Monaco on
Friday to mark the 700th anniversary of the principality, during
which Monaco's Prince Rainier III asked Chirac to help his country
enter the European monetary union at the same time as France.
</P>
