<DOCNO> XIE19970726.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Typhoon Strikes Western Japan, Paralyzing Traffic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 26 (Xinhua) -- A powerful typhoon struck western
Japan this evening, drenching wide areas with heavy rains and
paralyzing land, air and sea traffic, Japanese media reported.
</P>
<P>
The center of the typhoon, the season's ninth, was located at 3
p.m. about 50 kilometers southeast of Cape Muroto on the southern
tip of eastern Shikoku Island, the smallest of Japan's four main
islands, the Meteorological Agency said.
</P>
<P>
Packing winds of up to 144 kilometers per hour, the storm was
moving north-northwest at a speed of 20 kph.
</P>
<P>
The agency said the storm, the third to directly strike the
Japanese archipelago this year, has an atmospheric pressure of 965
hectopascals at its center.
</P>
<P>
The typhoon forced the cancellation of more than 300 domestic
air flights linking western Japan with capital Tokyo and other
parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
It also forced the suspension of bullet train services between
Osaka and Fukuoka, southwestern Japan, on the Sanyo Shinkansen
line. Almost all ferry services in western and southwestern Japan
were also canceled.
</P>
<P>
By this evening, the center of the typhoon is expected to reach
eastern Shikoku or the nearby waters, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
The agency warned of strong winds and heavy rains until the
typhoon travels across western Japan through the Sea of Japan
early Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
