<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian President Meets Arafat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and
Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat held a
meeting in Alexandria, 220 kilometers north of Cairo, this
morning, the Egyptian MENA news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
This is the second meeting between the two leaders on the
stalled Mideast peace process within a week in the Egypt's second
largest city.
</P>
<P>
The peace process has remained paralyzed since Israel began
building thousands of homes for Jews in the hilltop Har Homa on
the brink of East Jerusalem in March.
</P>
<P>
Their talks are also believed to focus on the Israeli decision
giving the green light for more settlement activities in the
occupied East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
In a move blasted by Arafat as a "declaration of war," Israel's
Jerusalem City Council decided late on Thursday to build a Jewish
settler enclave in the 11,000-strong Arab neighborhood of Ras
Al-Amoud in the heart of East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has warned that such a decision, combined with the Har
Homa building controversy, will kill the peace process and foil
ongoing efforts.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who arrived in the Mediterranean city this morning
following his European trip, is believed to brief the Egyptian
leader the outcome of his talks with Israeli Foreign Minister
David Levy, Labor Party leader Ehud Barak and European Union
foreign ministers in the past few days.
</P>
<P>
As a part of a European bid to advance Israeli-Palestinian
peace moves, the EU brokered the Levy-Arafat meeting in Brussels,
the highest level contact between the Palestinian and Israeli
sides in the five-month-old peace crisis.
</P>
<P>
Today's meeting will be followed up by an enlarged
Egyptian-Palestinian meeting in Cairo on Sunday to evaluate the
present peace situation. Egypt is expected to host a tripartite
summit grouping Mubarak, Arafat and Jordan's King Hussein by the
end of this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
