<HEADLINE> Romania, Moldova to Form Joint Peace-Keeping Troops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Romania and Moldova have decided
to form a joint battalion for peace-keeping purposes, Moldova's
Defense Minister Valer Pasat said here during his two-day visit.
</P>
<P>
Pasat, who was here on a visit from July 24-25, told reporters
that military experts of the two neighboring countries will work
out details of the formation of the peace-keeping force in
September.
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed that the battalion will not be deployed in
the east bank of the Dnestr River in Moldova.
</P>
<P>
An agreement on cooperation in military transportation was
signed during the visit.
</P>
<P>
Pasat also held talks with his Romanian counterpart, Victor
Babiuc, on cooperation in the field of military education.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers also discussed regional and European
security, Romania's bid to join the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization and cooperation between Moldova and NATO. 
</P>
