<HEADLINE> TAZARA Launches Marketing Drive to Boost Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 26 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzania Zambia Railway
Authority (tazara) has launched an aggressive marketing drive
aimed at boosting its business in Zambia, South Africa and the
Democratic Republic of Congo, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Moving his ministry's 1997/98 budget estimates at the National
Assembly in Dodoma on Friday, the Minister of Communications and
Transport, William Kusila, said the strategy would involve
strengthening ties with the Zambia Railways Corporation and firms
in South Africa and the Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
The minister said jointly with the Tanzania Harbours Authority
(THA), TAZARA was now exploring new markets and intends to open
an office for its representative in Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
Kusila also told the house that the authority was implementing
a commercialization program which include workers retrenchment,
establishment of computerised management information system and
work study.
</P>
<P>
He said in the 1995/96 TAZARA performed badly compared with
the previous year. However, he said the cargo transported by it
increased by 4 percent from 636,188 transported in 1994 to
662,523 in 1995/96.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on passengers, he said TAZARA experienced a big
drop of 20 percent from 1.8 million travelled in 1994/95 down to
1.5 million in 1995/96.
</P>
<P>
He said in 1995/96, TAZARA suffered 1.4 billion Tanzania
Shillings (about 2.3 million US Dollars) loss compared to 500
million T.Shs. (about 830,000 Dollars) profit realized in the
1994/95.
</P>
<P>
The minister said shortage of locomotives and wagons was a
major factor for the poor performance of TAZARA and that the
authority's management was not efficient enough in handling the
operations under the stiff commercial competititon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
