<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe, U.S. Sign Extradition Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe and the United States
yesterday signed an extradition treaty, the first such agreement
Zimbabwe has entered outside the Commonwealth and one to help the
country fight growing international crime.
</P>
<P>
Outgoing U.S. ambassador to Zimbabwe Johnnie Carson and
Zimbabwe's Foreign Affairs Minister Stan Mudenge signed the
treaty.
</P>
<P>
The treaty is only the second that the U.S. has signed with an
African country after the U.S.-Liberia extradition treaty of
1932.
</P>
<P>
Mudenge said, "with the increase in trans-boundary crimes the
world over, such as drug trafficking and money laundering, there
is need for a concerted effort at a global level to combat and
eliminate such a global menace."
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe and the U.S. had taken at least three years
negotiating for the treaty.
</P>
<P>
Carson said the signing of the treaty was testimony of the
high esteem the U.S. regards the Zimbabwean judiciary.
</P>
<P>
"The Zimbabwean judiciary is renowned worldwide for its
courage and independence. It is our faith and confidence in the
impartiality and professionalism of your courts which made this
treaty possible," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
