<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-26 07:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Third Australian Athlete Dies of Injury in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 26 (Xinhua) -- The third Australian athlete
participating in the 15th Maccabiah Games in Israel died of
injuries today in the tragedy of pedestrian bridge collapse,
according to the state-run Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
Elizabeth Savinsky, 48, Australian bridge champion, died in a
hospital in Afula early this morning.
</P>
<P>
A pedestrian bridge collapsed at the opening of the 15th
Maccabiah Games in the National Stadium, Ramat Gan, at night of
July 14, sending a group of Australian athletes plummeting into
the Yarkon River.
</P>
<P>
Gregory Small, 36, and Yetty Bennett, 50, died in the tragic
event. Savinsky had been among the 66 injured.
</P>
<P>
Her condition had deteriorated due to infection in her lungs
apparently caused by pollution in the Yarkon River. She had been
flown by a helicopter to Afula hospital immediately to be
connected to a special lung machine.
</P>
<P>
Her family were at her bedside Friday night as doctors made
their last efforts to save her life.
</P>
<P>
The games closed Thursday night. A pallor of sadness hung
over the closing ceremony at Latrun in Jerusalem, a usually
festive occasion.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the ceremony, Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
referred to the accident as "tragic and senseless." But he
added that "the horror did not stop the games."
</P>
<P>
According to the findings presented by a special investigating
committee, a chain of negligence, from faulty planning through
incompetent building, was blamed on all parties involved in the
collapse of the footbridge specially built for the Maccabiah
Games. No persons have so far been indicted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
