<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Find Way to Determine Giant Panda Pregnancy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have made a
breakthrough in ascertaining pregnancy in giant pandas.
</P>
<P>
The Giant Panda Breeding Research Center in this capital of
southwest China's Sichuan Province has employed enzyme-linked
immunosorbent assay (ELISA) for pregnancy testing for pandas, the
first success in this field.
</P>
<P>
According to an ELISA test, scientists can determine pregnancy
with an error rate of under five percent. They can also predict
the date of delivery.
</P>
<P>
"The ELISA method is safe and easy to operate," said Prof. Li
Guanghuan of the Center, adding that the result can be ready after
only a couple of hours.
</P>
<P>
In addition, after being treated with this method giant pandas
show an increased birth rate of 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the reason the giant panda is endangered is
its low reproductive ability.
</P>
<P>
During their yearly three-to-five-day oestrus period, mature
female giant pandas have no obvious change of vulva or any
distinctive behavior, according to experts.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, fake pregnancy of some prevents scientists from
appropriate determination.
</P>
<P>
Since the first artificial reproduction of a giant panda in
China in 1963, scientists have made many achievements in
collecting male giant pandas' sperm, artificial insemination and
breeding giant panda cubs.
</P>
<P>
However, scientists still found it difficult to determine
mating time and pregnancy before the new ELISA test was developed.
</P>
<P>
A mature female giant panda can become pregnant once a year if
she successfully mates with a male.
</P>
<P>
The giant panda remains one of the most endangered species on
earth, with its population standing at about 1,000, most of whom
live in western China's Sichuan, Gansu and Shaanxi provinces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
