<DOCNO> XIE19970726.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Asks U.S. Not to Let Taiwan Issue Interfere </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PETALING JAYA, Malaysia, July 26 (Xinhua) -- China today asked
the United States not to allow the Taiwan question to interfere
with relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint press conference with U.S. Secretary of
State Madeline Albright here before they were to hold talks on
questions including Cambodia, Chinese Foreign Minister Qian Qichen
said the question of Taiwan has always been the core issue in
Sino-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his appreciation of the fact that President Bill
Clinton, Albright and other U.S. officials have repeatedly
reiterated the U.S. commitment to the observance of the one-China
policy and the three joint communiques.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the U.S. side will honor this commitment and
handle the question of Taiwan cautiously and properly in order to
prevent the question of Taiwan from interfering again with the
improvement and growth of Sino-U.S. relations," he said.
</P>
<P>
Qian noted that since the beginning of this year, ties between
the two countries on the whole have maintained a good momentum of
growth.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has returned to the motherland smoothly and China's
most-favored-nation status in trade with the United States has
been renewed for this year, he said.
</P>
<P>
At present, he added, both sides are making vigorous
preparations for Chinese President Jiang Zemin's visit to the
United States in the coming fall.
</P>
<P>
"I expect to have frank and in-depth exchange of views with
Madam Secretary of State on Sino-U.S. relations and issues of
common interest," said Qian, who has met with Albright four times
this year.
</P>
<P>
On China's accession to the World Trade Organization (WTO),
Qian said it is in China's interests and also in the interests of
the international community including the United States.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out China has already made tremendous effort for
joining the WTO and hoped that the U.S. side will demonstrate
pragmatism and flexibility and solve this problem as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of nuclear proliferation, Qian said China has always
adopted a serious and responsible attitude toward the matter and
has strictly fulfilled its international obligations. "China has
no intention to carry out proliferation nor has it the political
and economic needs to do so."
</P>
<P>
On the human rights question, Qian declared, "We stand ready to
have dialogue with others in order to better understand each other
and seek common ground while shelving differences."
</P>
<P>
"However, dialogue must take place on the basis of equality and
mutual respect," he stressed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
