<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Courier Beats Krajicek for Semis in Infiniti Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 25 (Xinhua) -- American Jim Courier defeated
twice champion Richard Krajicek of the Netherlands in straight
sets to advance to the semifinals of the 303,000 Infiniti Open
men's tennis tournament in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
The former world No. 1, twice French Open champion in 1991 and
1992, recorded his quarterfinal victory of 7-6 (7-5), 7-5 late
Friday night against Krajicek, the 1996 Wimbledon champion.
</P>
<P>
Also sailing further to the semifinals were top-seeded Goran
Ivanisevic of Croatia, second-seeded Thomas Enqvist of Sweden and
Guillaume Raoux of France.
</P>
<P>
With his forehand winners and crisp volleys, Courier was up 3-1
in the first set after Krajicek double faulted.
</P>
<P>
Yet, Krajicek broke back in the seventh game and held his serve
to send the set into a tiebreaker which Courier won 7-5.
</P>
<P>
Courier captured the only break in the second set with his
backhand service return to go up 6-5.
</P>
<P>
With the win, Courier enjoyed a 7-1 record against Krajicek,
and will next play Ivanisevic who defeated Byron Black of Zimbabwe
7-6 (7-3), 6-2 in 72 minutes.
</P>
<P>
In other quarters of the day, Enqvist blasted past Kenneth
Carlsen of Denmark 6-3, 7-5 while and third-seeded Mark
Philippoussis of Australia became the victim of Raoux by losing
the match 7-6 (7-5), 6-4. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
