<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Czech Republic Closes Embassies to Save Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, July 25 (Xinhua) -- The Czech Republic, facing a huge
budget deficit this year, has decided to shut down seven of its
111 embassies and consulates worldwide to cut costs, reports said
today.
</P>
<P>
Among those to be shut down include the embassies in Yemen,
Libya, Uruguay and Algeria.
</P>
<P>
The country's budget deficit this year had risen to 12.2
billion koruna (some 407 million U.S. dollars) by the end of May,
and foreign exchange reserves dropping to 10 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry budget this year has been cut from 4
billion koruna (121.1 million dollars) to 3.3 billion koruna (100
million dollars) and will further decrease to 2.6 billion koruna
(78.78 million dollars) next year.
</P>
<P>
To deal with the shortfall, the government has streamlined the
public sector workforce, suspended the construction of luxury
buildings and even canceled routine state banquets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970726.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coffee Beans, Vietnam's Second Most Valuable Crop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Coffee beans has became Vietnam's
second most valuable crop after rice, which gives the country an
annual export turnover of 400 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam is ranked eighth in coffee acreage and sixth in
production among the 70 coffee-producing countries in the world.
</P>
<P>
Coffee acreage in the country has increased to the present
230,000 ha, of which 180,000 ha yield beans.
</P>
<P>
In the 1996-97 crop, Vietnam harvested a record of 300,000 tons
of coffee beans, of which some 248,000 tons were shipped abroad in
the first six months of this year.
</P>
<P>
The country plans to export 280,000 tons this year, trying to
become Asia's second largest coffee exporter after Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
As many as 320,000 tons of coffee beans are expected to be
harvested from the 1997-98 crop and of the amount, 310,000 tons
are going for export.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's coffee is exported to nearly 40 countries with the
United States, Germany and Japan being the three biggest buyers.
</P>
<P>
However, Vietnam's coffee is less competitive than Indian and
Indonesian coffee in the world market due to its low quality,
which results in losses of millions of dollars each year.
</P>
<P>
What is worse is that 90 percent of Vietnam's coffee-growing
areas is covered by the robusta strain while only 10 percent was
by arabica, whose value is 1.5 to two times higher than robusta.
</P>
<P>
A further 3,000 ha will be planted with arabica coffee in the
1997-98 crop, so that arabica coffee area will make up 30 percent
of the total acreage by the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam plans to improve coffee processing technology and
expand arabica coffee-growing acreage in the coming years in order
to raise export coffee quality.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the country is accelerating preparations for
joining the world coffee producers' association in order to get
timely information on the world coffee market and the latest
approaches to planting and processing technologies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
