<HEADLINE> Court Upholds Ruling on Plagiarism Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 26 (Xinhua) -- After four years of court debate,
the complier and publisher of the popular Contemporary Chinese
Dictionary finally won the lawsuit against Wang Tongyi and Hainan
Publishing House accused of plagiarizing the dictionary.
</P>
<P>
Their verdict was given by the First Beijing People's
Intermediate Court last December, and was completely upheld by the
Beijing's High Court on Thursday after refuting the defendants'
appeal, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
In an earlier verdict by the intermediate court, Wang and
Hainan Publishing House were ruled plagiarizing the dictionary and
two others, compiled by the Institute of Linguistics of the
Chinese Academy of Social Sciences and published by the Commercial
Press.
</P>
<P>
The verdict ordered Wang and Hainan Publishing House to stop
their infringement activities and stop selling plagiarized copies
of the dictionaries, and pay the complier and publisher of the
Contemporary Chinese Dictionary 147,931 yuan each for damages.
</P>
<P>
The defendants were also ordered to cover the lawsuit fees of
the complier and the publisher.
</P>
<P>
Wang and the Hainan Publishing House appealed to Beijing
People's High Court in January.  
</P>
</TEXT>
