<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Approves Extension ESAF Credit for Guinea-Bissau </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 25 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) today approved a request of the government of Guinea-Bissau
to extend the 3-year arrangement under the Enhanced Structural
Adjustment Facility (ESAF) ending in March, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The IMF also agreed the country's request to increase the
amount by about 1.4 million U.S. dollars. This will provide about
6.5 million dollars to back the Guinea-Bissau's economic program
for 1997/98.
</P>
<P>
The IMF okayed a three-year ESAF credit for Guinea-Bissau
equivalent to about 13 million dollars in January 1995.
</P>
<P>
The ESAF is a concessional IMF facility for assisting member
countries that are undertaking economic reform programs to
strengthen their balance of payments and improve their growth
prospects. The ESAF credits carry an annual interest of 0.5
percent and are repayable over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
The 1997/98 economic program seeks annual GDP growth of about 5
percent, to contain annual inflation at about 10 percent in 1997
and 7 percent in 1998 as well as to reduce the external current
account deficit to 18 percent of GDP in 1997 and to 16.4 percent
of GDP in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Guinea-Bissau joined the IMF in March, 1977. Its quota is about
14 million dollars and its outstanding use of IMF financing
currently totals about 10 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
