<HEADLINE> Nicaragua May Invite World Guarantors to Peace Dialogue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, July 25 (Xinhua) -- The group mediating Nicaragua's
so-called national dialogue may invite international guarantors to
the talks despite President Arnoldo Aleman's opposition, fueling
hopes that the Sandinistas, the main opposition, may also take
part.
</P>
<P>
The national dialogue, proposed by Aleman to resolve a dispute
over properties confiscated by the left-wing Sandinistas during
their 1979-1990 rule, began Monday without the participation of
Daniel Ortega's Sandinista Front (FSLN).
</P>
<P>
The presence of international guarantors is one of the
conditions set by the Sandinistas for participation in the
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
Aleman demanded that the Sandinistas surrender the properties
they confiscated in their final days of government in 1990 or
compensate people for them.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Sandinistas have accused Aleman of trying to
kick thousands of families who received confiscated land off their
property and return it to their former owners. Aleman has denied
the charges.
</P>
<P>
The mediating group said they may invite international
guarantors to the dialogue after meeting international diplomats
from the United States, Europe and South America Thursday who
supported the idea.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats said they would not insist on the participation of
the Sandinistas in the dialogue, but as a show of good will, the
Sandinistas' proposal about the guarantors should be on the agenda
of the dialogue.
</P>
<P>
However, Aleman has repeatedly rejected the idea of inviting
international guarantors, saying only Nicaraguans can find
solutions to their own problems.
</P>
<P>
The Central American country is tense after weeks of clashes
between protesters and police in late June and early this month
left 150 people injured.
</P>
<P>
Ostensibly, the battle was over student demands for an increase
in education spending. But behind it was the struggle between
leftist Sandinistas and the conservative government.
</P>
<P>
The struggle began when Sandinistas claimed balloting in
several districts in last October elections was fraudulent. Aleman
defeated the FSLN's Daniel Ortega by a narrow margin.
</P>
<P>
The tension has prompted fears that the country could slide
back into an open war that plagued the country in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
The Sandinistas seized power in a 1979 revolution, ending four
decades of dictatorship. U.S.-supported Contra rebels tried in
vain to overthrow them.
</P>
<P>
Then, Violeta Chamorro replaced Ortega as president after a
landslide victory over the Sandinistas in 1990, ending a
eight-year civil war. She was succeeded by Aleman in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Although Chamorro entered into a pact with the Sandinistas to
lay the basis for coexistence, Aleman has insisted he will never
make a pact with the front. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
