<HEADLINE> Russia Imposes Tax on Foreign Currency Purchases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 25 (Xinhua) -- In an effort to boost confidence in
the Russian currency ruble, Russian President Boris Yeltsin signed
a law today that will impose a 0.5 percent tax on purchases of
cash foreign currency.
</P>
<P>
The tax is expected to bring about 1 trillion rubles (172
million U.S. dollars) in revenue to the government this year.
</P>
<P>
The tax, which failed to win parliamentary approval in the 1997
budget, will apply to all foreign currencies and is expected to
lead to a slight increase in commission charges by banks.
</P>
<P>
Sales of foreign currency for rubles are not taxed.
Transactions between commercial banks also are not covered.
</P>
<P>
Years of sluggish economic growth and high inflation has
damaged Russians' confidence in their currency, and many people
have scrambled to hold their savings in foreign currency cash.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank figures show that Russians bought a total of 51.57
billion U.S. dollars in cash from commercial banks last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
