<HEADLINE> Three Gorges Still Scenic After Dam Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, July 26 (Xinhua) -- A group of local tourism experts
recently asked people not to be so eager for travel agencies'
"Farewell Three Gorges" tours, because the area will maintain its
beauty even after the huge dam is built there.
</P>
<P>
The central Chinese area where the multi-billion yuan
hydro-electric power project is now under construction on the
middle reaches of the Yangtze River, will continue to be a tourist
paradise, with some new scenic sites, they said.
</P>
<P>
The China Three Gorges Construction Corporation and the Tourism
Administration of Hubei Province expressed this view at a recent
meeting in Wuhan, capital of Hubei.
</P>
<P>
No tourist spots will be affected when the river is blocked for
dam work by November of this year, and out of 39 historic and
scenic sites, only 13 will be submerged by 2012 when the project
is completed, with a water level of 175 m above sea-level.
</P>
<P>
The government has taken steps to preserve some of the
important historic and tourist sites that will be under water.
</P>
<P>
Experts caution tourists about being misled by some travel
agencies who are trying to get people to join their "farewell"
trips, because the existing tourist sites will not all be
submerged until 2003, when the second phase of the project comes
to an end.  
</P>
