<HEADLINE> Thailand's Fiscal Deficit Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 26 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government's fiscal
position has improved with its fiscal deficit continuing to
decline, local newspaper Bangkok Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
By the end of June, the ninth month of the current 1997 fiscal
year (from October 1, 1996 to September 30, 1997), the deficit
fell to 12 billion Baht (465 million U.S. dollars), from 50
billion Baht (2 billion U.S. dollars) at the end of the first
quarter (December 1996) of the 1997 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The deficit is expected to fall further to about 10 billion
Baht (312.5 million U.S. dollars) by the end of the fiscal year,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The improved outlook is attributed to high revenue collection.
</P>
<P>
June was the second month in a row that the government enjoyed
a fiscal surplus. The surplus of the month was 29.5 billion Baht
(1.14 billion U.S. dollars). 
