<HEADLINE> Central Government Aids Economic Development in Northwest Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region, a
landlocked area in northwest China, has made headway in economic
growth with the aid of state funding.
</P>
<P>
According to government statistics, Ningxia's Gross Domestic
Product (GDP) in 1996 was two percentage points higher than the
country's average level of 9.7 percent, which indicates its
economy is on the rise.
</P>
<P>
Ningxia is the sole autonomous region inhabited by the Hui
people. Located in the northwest mountainous areas, its traffic
conditions and economic conditions lag far behind eastern areas.
</P>
<P>
Now that China has started to shift its development focus
westward, the central government has invested heavily in the fixed
assets reformation in the area to reinforce the development of
local basic industries.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the central government invested some 7.2 billion
yuan in the area, an increase of 14.7 percent over the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
The funding has guaranteed the construction of key projects in
Ningxia, including the Lingxin Mine, capable of producing 2.4
million tons annually in the Lingwu mining area; the fourth unit
of a hydroelectric power station with an installed capacity of
300,000 kw. A number of major projects are now under construction.
</P>
<P>
Some traffic projects, such as Baoji-Zhongwei Railway, Hedong
Airport in Yinchuan, capital of the region, and a road tunnel in
the Liupan Mountain are also underway, and will greatly improve
the poor traffic conditions.
</P>
<P>
A local official said that the central government used to
appropriate 30 million yuan each year for a project in the Ningxia
mountainous areas to help the local people gain access to drinking
water.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the central government granted three billion yuan to
the water channel project, and also reclaimed wasteland and built
irrigation facilities.
</P>
<P>
The efforts have paid off: Over 500,000 people in Xihaigu
Prefecture have moved above the poverty line. Last year, an
unprecedented grain harvest brought to Ningxia 2.5 billion tons of
grain, representing an increase of 26.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Ningxia has become a major grain and non-staple food producer
in northwest China, the official said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
