<HEADLINE> Satellite to Help Monitor Oceanic Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Beijing plans to launch its first
satellite to probe oceanic environmental elements by 2000,
according to today's "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
Environmental elements to be surveyed include density of
chlorophyll, the content of suspended grits, soluble organic
substances, water temperature, pollutants and topography under
shallow seas.
</P>
<P>
The satellite's remote sensing is regarded worldwide as the
most effective means, and will become the main way to probe the
oceanic environment.
</P>
<P>
Twelve such satellites have been launched or are to be
launched. Three come from the United States, four from Japan and
the others from Europe, Russia, India, South Korea and China's
Taibei. 
</P>
</TEXT>
