<HEADLINE> Thailand's Exports Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's exports in the first
five months of the year were worth 587 billion Baht (22.95 billion
U.S. dollars), up 2.3 percent over the same period of last year,
according to a Commerce Ministry source.
</P>
<P>
The trade deficit shrank by 29.4 percent to 144 billion Baht
(5.58 billion U.S. dollars), although imports rose by 5.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The source said the export figures showed the promise of a
recovery, with exporters confirming that orders have been placed
throughout the year.
</P>
<P>
Though there was only a slight improvement in exports in the
past five months, the floating of the Baht would help exports
reach the 10 percent growth target and finish the year at 1.4
trillion Baht (43.75 billion dollars), the source said.
</P>
<P>
However, some exporters complained about the Baht float after
some local suppliers stopped supplying them with imported raw
materials due to higher import costs.  
