<HEADLINE> Costa Rica Heeds Complaint from Mexican Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rica officials have said
that the procedural difficulties faced by some Mexican companies
will not lead to the withdrawal of foreign investment out of the
country.
</P>
<P>
Three Mexican companies -- Triturados Basalticos (Tribasa),
Ingenieros Civiles Asociados (ICA) and Mabe -- have complained
that their experiences in Costa Rica are not very positive.
</P>
<P>
A spokesmen for the three Mexican firms said that the
cancellations of biddings already won are an invitation for not
returning.
</P>
<P>
In response to the complaint, Costa Rican Minister of Economy
Jose Leon Desanti and Minister of Planning Leonardo Garnier
conceded that there are many obstacles to foreign investment in
the country.
</P>
<P>
But efforts have been made over last 10 years to eliminate
them, said Garnier.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Trade Vice Minister Carlos Murillo said that what
happened with the Tribasa construction firm and Mabe could happen
with companies of any other country.
</P>
<P>
First Vice President Rodrigo Oreamuno said that government will
try to solve all the cases after careful examination.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the analysis of the free trade agreement with Mexico,
which came into force in January 1995 is expected to complete in
the next few weeks, Costa Rican authorities said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
