<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Father Gives Part Of Liver To Save Daughter's Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Yu Faqin, who was born into a
farmer's family in a small village in central China's Henan
Province in 1987, had trouble with her liver since she was only
two years old.
</P>
<P>
She was frequently bed-ridden with high fever and jaundice, and
was carried around to various hospitals on her parents' backs as
early as she could remember.
</P>
<P>
Her disease also cost her parents a fortune and they sold their
cattle and property just to cover medical costs.
</P>
<P>
Last November, when the disease turned worse, her parents took
her to Xijing Hospital, in Xi'an, capital of Northwest China's
Shaanxi Province, where she was diagnosed as having congenital
cystic dilatation of the intrahepatic duct, an advanced stage of
liver disease causing cirrhosis of the liver.
</P>
<P>
The only way to save her life was a liver transplant,
preferably part of one of her parents' liver. The cost of the
operation would be more than 200,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Her parents could not afford to pay anything near that amount,
but hospital authorities decided to do the operation for free. A
team of doctors from 19 departments was assembled and medicine
ordered from other parts of China and overseas, and a 200,000-yuan
microscope was brought by air from Guangzhou, capital of south
China's Guangdong Province, for the delicate operation.
</P>
<P>
The 13-hour operation, which was done on June 30 under the
supervision of a Japanese doctor, involved transplanting a third
of her father's liver to the 10-year-old girl. Liver transplants
had only been done for eight years in China, and none had been
successful before.
</P>
<P>
She lapsed into a coma after the operation, but on the third
day she woke up. The liver graft began to function on the seventh
day, and by the ninth, it had grown a centimeter in diameter. Half
a month after the operation, the girl could manage to eat some
porridge and noodles and played with the hospital staff. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970726.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Speeds up Highway Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 26 (Xinhua) -- China is speeding the construction
of a nationwide highway network to ease the "transport bottleneck"
holding its continuous economic development.
</P>
<P>
According to a cross-century blueprint drafted by the Ministry
of Communications, 12 major highways with a total mileage of
35,000 km - five on a north-south axis and seven on an east-west
axis - will be built across the country, linking all the 31
provincial and autonomous regional capitals, as well as the four
municipalities on the Chinese mainland.
</P>
<P>
The highways will also connect all cities each with a
population of more than one million and 93 percent of the cities
each with a population of more than half a million, benefiting
about 600 million people of the country, today's China Daily
reported.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Cao You'an, deputy director of the ministry's
Planning Department, as saying that the ministry plan was set into
motion in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
One-day return journeys within distances of 400-500 km and
one-way trips of 800-1,000 km will be made possible on the new
highway system, the official said.
</P>
<P>
About 4,000 km of the national trunk highways of the network
have already been completed. They include some well-known
expressways and first-class highways for the exclusive use of
automobiles.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest figures from the Ministry of
Communications, by the end of 1996, the country had built 1.18
million km of highways, including 3,400 km of expressways.
</P>
</TEXT>
