<HEADLINE> New Albanian FM Pledges to Improve Ties With Neighbors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Albania's newly-appointed Foreign
Minister today pledged that his country will seek to build up good
neighborly relations with its neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference after the sworn-in of the new
government led by the Socialist Party, Paskal Milo stressed that
improving relations with its neighbors is much better than
lingering in the state of Cold War.
</P>
<P>
Milo, who is vice-chairman of the Socialist Party and a
well-known expert on international affairs, said that in order to
create a relaxed international environment for Albania the
government should, first of all, develop good relations with its
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
But for some historical and other reasons, there have been
tensions and unease in the relations between Albania and its
neighbors, he said.
</P>
<P>
Milo said that the new government will pursue a new policy of
resolving differences and conflicts between neighbors through
dialogue and peaceful means, which will help promote good-will
between Albania and Italy, Greece, Macedonia and the Republic of
Serbia of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
On the relations between his country and Serbia, Milo called on
both countries to usher in a new chapter without any prejudice.
</P>
<P>
But it does not mean that Albania will cease to back the
interests of the ethnic Albanians in neighboring countries,
especially in Kosovo, he added.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Albania and Serbia became restrained after
Albania supported the independence movement of Kosovo led by
ethnic Albanians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
