<HEADLINE> Mine Cleanup Resumed in North Costa Rica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rican authorities announced
today that experts of the country have resumed the cleanup of mines
in the areas bordering Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
The operation is undertaken by 26 sappers trained by two
Colombian and one Brazilian experts, said a Public Security
Ministry spokesman.
</P>
<P>
It is officially estimated that some 5,000 mines were laid the
border areas of the country by rebels, who combatted the
Sandinista regime of Nicaragua during 1980s.
</P>
<P>
The cleanup started in last October and was suspended later
because a Public Security Ministry helicopter used by the experts
needed some repairing. 
</P>
