<DOCNO> XIE19970726.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 25 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic briefs from Latin American countries in the week:
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- The Argentine budget deficit was 1.31 billion
pesos (1.31 billion U.S. dollars) in the first half of
this year, a 6.5 percent reduction compared to the 1.4 billion
pesos forecast.
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- A cooperation agreement signed by the
Colombian oil company Ecopetrol and its Venezuelan counterpart
PDVSA establishes that both sides will jointly study the
geological evolution and the oil system of the area between
Casanare in Colombia and Barinas in Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chilean book exports will reach a total of 47
million U.S. dollars in 1997, a 30.5 percent increase over 1996,
said the Chilean Book Chamber.
</P>
<P>
It is foreseen that book exports will keep its rising trend in
1998 since investments of 80 million dollars are expected for
that year
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Mexican honey output dropped 40 percent in the
past two years because of a plague known as varroa of the apiaries,
said Enrique Carrillo, National Beekeepers Union president.
</P>
<P>
A production of 25,000 tons of honey has been lost from 1995 upto
this year and before the plague, Mexico produced 55,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Costa Rica might close the year with a 4 percent
budget deficit, two percentage points higher than the 2 percent
recorded in the first half of this year, said Finance Minister
Francisco de Paula Gutierrez.
</P>
<P>
If the forecast comes true, the 1997 deficit will be 90
billion dollar colons (386.2 million U.S. dollars), the finance
minister said.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- Port Sandino on the Pacific coast of Nicaragua was
reinaugurated after the conclusion of restorations. The port is
located 69 kilometers west of Managua.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil's export of coffee increased 140 percent and
soybeans 39 percent during the first half of this year, compared
to the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Coffee exports reached 1.385 billion U.S. dollars and soybeans
3.19 billion dollars, said the Industry, Commerce and Tourism
Ministry. 
</P>
