<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Takes ABC Champions Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Regal of Hong Kong rallied from a
six-point halftime deficit to beat Kia Motor of South Korea 64-59
on Friday to win the eighth Asian Basketball Confederation's
Champions Cup.
</P>
<P>
Led by Clifford Aaron Reed, Kia broke open a 12-12 game after
10 minutes and led 32-26 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
But Reed injured his leg four minutes before the intermission,
forcing him out of the game and allowing Regal to dominate the
second half.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong team refused to play the fast game Kia is known
for and controlled the tempo of the final.
</P>
<P>
"Our strategy was to slow the game down and keep it low
scoring, about 60 or 70 points. Then we had a chance to win," team
chairman Stanley Au said, "If we came out running, Kia is too fast
a team. We would have run out of energy by the end of the game."
</P>
<P>
Yung Kam-wah, who flew in for the team's last two games, was
the leading scorer with 22 points, scoring often in the final
minutes to break a deadlocked game.
</P>
<P>
Tournament MVP Wayman Strickland contributed 12 points and five
assists.
</P>
<P>
Third place was won by the Aspac team of Indonesia with a 78-52
victory over Isuzu of Japan, and Tanduay Gold of the Philippines
finished fifth with a 94-89 victory over China's Hongshan 94-89.
</P>
</TEXT>
