<HEADLINE> South China Province Out of Doldrums With Better Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGDONG, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Guangdong Province in south
China had steady economic growth in the first half, pulling it
out of the doldrums, according to Governor Lu Ruihua.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong's industrial production amounted to 309.8 billion
yuan, up 19.3 percent from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The spring harvest produced almost a million tons, a rise of
21.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Price hikes slowed down during the period, while the retail
price and consumer retail price indexes were up 0.2 and 2.9
percent, respectively, both lower than the national average.
</P>
<P>
Exports totaled 25.6 billion US dollars, a year-on-year rise of
25 percent, and local revenues were 19 billion yuan, up 25.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong drew up its 20-year development program in 1992. Its
GDP had quadruppled eight years before the year 2000 set by the
plan. During the Eighth Five-Year Plan, economic growth averaged
19 percent, six percentage points more than the proposed target.
</P>
<P>
In the second half of this year it will put more emphasis on
rebuilding the state-owned sector, improving agriculture,
eradicating poverty in mountainous areas, and ensuring economic
growth by concentrating on family planning and environmental
protection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
