<HEADLINE> Agriculture Must Be Put on AFTA Agenda: Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The Southern Common Market
(Mercosur) countries insist that agriculture and textile products
should be on the agenda in negotiations on the creation of the
American Free Trade Area.
</P>
<P>
The four Mercosur countries -- Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and
Uruguay -- will reject any U.S. boycott to talks on agriculture
products, Brazilian Foreign Affairs Ministry undersecretary Jose
Botafogo Gonzalves was quoted as saying by the press in today's
issues.
</P>
<P>
The four countries want the creation of two specific groups to
negotiate textile and agriculture products during the creation of
AFTA, said Botafogo.
</P>
<P>
The purpose is to counteract the U.S. boycott to the entry of
agriculture and textile products into its market, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Agriculture is the sector in which we have most restrictions
in the U.S., Canadian and EU markets," he added.
</P>
<P>
International barriers to agriculture products cause a loss of
5 billion dollars to Brazil, said Brazilian authorities.
</P>
<P>
The next round of talks on the AFTA creation is foreseen for
July 29 in Costa Rica with the attendance of 34 vice commerce
ministers of the hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
Next week's meeting in Costa Rica will be the first of the
three that will precede the second summit of the Americas
scheduled for April, 1998 in Chile.
</P>
<P>
The issue of textile and agriculture products will be taken up
at these meetings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
