<HEADLINE> US Durable Goods Orders Up 2.3 Percent in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Factory orders for durable
goods in the U.S. increased by 2.3 percent last month, the U.S.
Commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that orders for durable goods, items
expected to last for three years and more, hit a record seasonally
adjusted 180.6 billion dollars in June.
</P>
<P>
It was the biggest gain since last January and the increase
followed a 0.4 percent decrease in May.
</P>
<P>
The durable goods increase was concentrated in transportation
equipment which were up by 7.5 percent. Military goods gained by
9.9 percent and primary metals such as steel increased by 0.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
Bookings for electrical equipment were unchanged and orders for
industrial machinery fell by 0.6 percent, the second consecutive
month of decline.
</P>
<P>
However, even excluding the volatile transportation sector,
orders were up 0.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Shipments of durable goods, a measure of current production,
climbed by 1.8 percent in June to a seasonally adjusted 179.1
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the backlog of unfilled orders rose 0.3 percent to
498.8 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
June's rebound showed that U.S. economic growth remains healthy
though subdued compared with the quick pace in the first quarter.
</P>
</TEXT>
