<HEADLINE> Clinton Calls for National Voluntary School Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 25 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today announced that 15 big-city school districts are joining his
program of voluntary standards, and called on more states to
follow suit, in a hope to upgrade the students' skills.
</P>
<P>
"I believe the single most important thing we can do to give
our children world-class education is to insist on high national
standards," the president said in a speech to the National
Association of Elementary School Principals.
</P>
<P>
Clinton was satisfied that some big cities, including New York,
Los Angeles, Chicago, Houston, Philadelphia and Seattle, have
joined the program.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of these school districts know that "this is an
historic, astonishing, wonderful moment in American education, and
I thank them for doing it," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has pushed states to enlist schools in a voluntary
program of testing and performance measures for grade-school
students starting in 1999 when the test becomes available. But
only six states have responded to his call so far.
</P>
<P>
He accused governors of "dragging their feet" and producing
inadequate support for national school standards.
</P>
<P>
"When we don't expect or encourage our children to learn, we
indirectly encourage them to fail," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
"we don't have to settle for second-class expectations or
second-class goals for any of our children," he stressed.
</P>
</TEXT>
