<HEADLINE> Sales of Existing Homes in US Down in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Sales of previously owned homes
in the U.S. declined by 2.6 percent in June but remained at a
healthy level, the U.S. National Association of Realtors reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the existing single-family homes sold at a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 4.14 million units last month
following an increase of 4.7 percent in May.
</P>
<P>
Regionally, sales of previously owned homes fell by 7.7 percent
in the Northeast and 6.4 percent in the West. They were unchanged
in the South and rose by 0.9 percent in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
The median price of an existing home in the U.S. was 127,200
dollars in June, up by 3.5 percent from a year ago. The median
price is the midpoint, meaning half homes sold for more and half
for less.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.S. mortgage rates continue to favor the homes
sales. Thirty-year, fixed-rate mortgages averaged 7.69 percent in
June, down from 7.94 percent in May, according to the U.S. Federal
Homes Loan Corporation recently. They have averaged 7.5 percent so
far this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
