<HEADLINE> Greece Decides to Deregulate National Power Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 25 (Xinhua) -- The Greek government today decided
during a cabinet meeting that the national electric power market
would be deregulated, making it possible for the private sector to
produce electric power, government spokesman Dimitris Reppas
announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after the cabinet meeting, Reppas said
that the institutional, organizing and administrative framework
governing the electric power market would have to be completed by
February 1999.
</P>
<P>
"This means that the private sector will be given the
possibility of producing electric power and that the Public Power
Corporation (DEH) will maintain public control," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that it was also decided that processes for linking
Greece with the European networks (cable with Italy) would be
speeded up and the institutional framework for the purchase of
electric power promoted in parliament by the end of the year.
</P>
