<HEADLINE> Another Group of Deaf Mexican Peddlers Found in US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 25 (Xinhua) -- U.S. immigration agents in
Sanford, North Carolina, have broken up an alleged ring similar to
one in New York City that forced deaf Mexicans to sell trinkets on
the street to earn money.
</P>
<P>
Fourteen deaf adults and three children in the case were taken
into custody, local media reports said.
</P>
<P>
The two brick houses are well known to neighbors, who said the
Mexicans peddled key chains and tiny American flags on streets and
outside supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
The deaf people didn't have complaints of beatings, but they
were being held captive and were forced to work and to turn over
the money and to bring in a minimum of money every day, Teodoro
Maus, Mexico's consul general in Atlanta, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Last week, police found in New York City that 57 people, most
of them unable to hear or speak, were living in two homes. The
group, including 12 children, was allegedly smuggled into the
United States to peddle trinkets on the subways and streets.
</P>
<P>
The alleged ringleader is still at large but seven other
Mexicans face charges including smuggling and extortion in the New
York City case. 
</P>
</TEXT>
