<HEADLINE> Annan Appoints New UN Transitional Administrator </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 25 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan today appointed William Walker of the United States as the
new United Nations Transitional Administrator for Eastern
Slavonia, Baranja and Western Sirmium, effective on August 1.
</P>
<P>
Walker, who will take over from Jacques Klein, was
vice-president of the United States National Defense College, and
before then, ambassador to El Salvador from 1988 to 1992.
Preceding that appointment, he served as deputy assistant
secretary of state for inter-American affairs, with responsibility
for United States relations with Central America and Panama.
</P>
<P>
In his 34 years as a foreign service officer, Walker served in
Peru, Brazil, El Salvador, Honduras and Bolivia. In domestic
postings, he was Argentine desk officer in the Department of State
from 1967-1968. He served with the Environmental Protection Agency
in San Francisco from 1972-1974 and was the State Department
Fellow at the Council of Foreign Relations in New York from
1977-1978. He also served as a foreign service inspector in the
Office of the Inspector General from 1978-1980.
</P>
<P>
Walker is married and had four children. He also speaks Spanish
and Portuguese. 
</P>
</TEXT>
