<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Auto Market Flat in the First Half </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 26 (Xinhua) -- China's automobile market remained
flat in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics from China's Ministry of
Machine-building Industry, the auto production topped 813,600
units in the first six months, a year-on-year rise of 7.28 percent
while sales reached 774,800 units, up 7.44 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the auto stock by the end of June hit 136,000 units,
a net increase of 26,000 units more than at the end of the first
quarter. Local analysts predicted the stock may go up in the
second six-month period.
</P>
<P>
According to local auto experts, the growth in both the
production and sales should be attributed to the booming market of
cars and mini-vehicles. Automakers in the period turned out
238,000 cars, or a rise of 22.99 percent, and sold 226,900, up
24.58 percent. The production of mini-buses topped 118,600,
increasing 34 percent; and the sales hit 108,100, a rise of 27.14
percent.
</P>
<P>
The FAW-Volkswagen Auto Corp. and Dongfeng Cietron Corp.,
China's two largest car ventures, grabbed more market shares in
the period. Their year-on-year growth registered 50 percent and
126 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The heavy-duty trucks and large buses also posted noteworthy
growth. Production and sales of heavy-duty trucks totaled 15,900
and 14,400 units, up 18.21 percent and 5.49 percent. Automakers
turned out 3,500 large buses and sold 2,900 units, up 54.84
percent and 59.34 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Production and sales of medium- and light-duty passenger
vehicles and trucks retained their downward trend in the period.
</P>
<P>
Of the seven major auto groups, both production and sales of
Shanghai Automotive Industry Group posted more than 20 percent
growth.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts said the performance of the others was just
"so-so."  
</P>
</TEXT>
