<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiangsu Remains Hot Spot for Overseas Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, July 26 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangsu Province
attracted the largest amount of overseas investment in the first
half of this year among China's provinces, according to
the latest statistics.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months the province attracted a total
contractual overseas investment of 5.133 billion US dollars, up 47
percent over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Suzhou, a leading tourist destination, attracted 2.364 billion
US dollars. Zhenjiang followed Suzhou by attracting 1.589 billion
US dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, more large projects funded by
transnational companies were set up in Jiangsu. The per-project
investment averaged 5.29 million US dollars, or 1.44 times more
than that of last year. The number of projects with investment of
more than 10 million US dollars each hit 137.
</P>
<P>
To name a few major projects, the Zhenjiang Jindong Paper
Corporation was given approval to form a venture with an
investment of 1.823 billion US dollars, and the Mercedes-Benz
Company of Germany invested 99.5 million US dollars in an
automobile manufacturing project in Yangzhou.
</P>
<P>
Other transnationals, such as Shell and Mitsubishi, funded 20
projects, the total investment of 17 of which exceeded 10 million
US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, more investors from developed countries and emerging
economies in Asia chose Jiangsu for their investments. Singapore,
ranked the first with 2.03 billion yuan in the first half of this
year. Other major investors included Japan, the United States, the
Republic of Korea and Britain.
</P>
<P>
Some 88 percent of overseas investment was poured into the
manufacturing sector, especially investment was injected into such
technology-intensive industries as chemicals, pharmaceuticals,
telecommunications and electricity.
</P>
<P>
It is also noteworthy that the province's agricultural sector
attracted 44.72 million US dollars in the same period.
</P>
<P>
The latest statistics also indicate that the overseas
investment actually utilized by the province was on a continual
rise. In the first six months it put 2.564 billion US dollars into
use, a rise of 25.6 percent compared to the same period of last
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
