<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Industry, Real Estate Magnets of Overseas Investment in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 26 (Xinhua) -- The industrial and real estate
sectors attracted 89 percent of overseas contractual investment in
this, China's largest economic metropolis, in the first six months
of this year, according to the latest statistics released by the
local government.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts consider that the investment trend is in line with
the target set for the city's future macro-economic mix. "Even though
more efforts have been paid to developing the tertiary sector,
industry at the current stage is still the cornerstone of the
local economy," a local economist said.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investors plan to take advantage of Shanghai's
existing infrastructure and skilled workers. More investment is
being poured into "economic pillars" such as telecommunications,
micro-electronics and domestic appliances. The number of projects
each with more than 10 million US dollars in investment reached 95
in the first half of the year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the largest-ever Sino-US project, the Shanghai GM
Corporation, a joint venture between the Shanghai Automotive
Industry Group and General Motors, is under construction at a cost
of 1.57 billion US dollars. Upon completion, the venture is to
produce 100,000 sedans annually.
</P>
<P>
As China has recently designated real estate as a new economic
sector for future development, more overseas capital is flowing
into Shanghai's real estate market.
</P>
<P>
In the Pudong New Area, overseas investors in the first six
months registered 317 projects with a total contractual investment
of 1.644 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Also in the first six months of this year, Shanghai approved
888 projects with contractual overseas investment totalling 2.27
billion US dollars. By the end of June Shanghai had approved an
aggregate of 16,583 overseas-funded projects.  
</P>
</TEXT>
